column168: Description Of Events

THIS PKG WAS FOUND IN AN UNLOAD TRAILER WITH A SMALL LEAK SPOT ON IT, (STAINING THE BOX.) UPON INSPECTION BY A CERTIFIED HAZMAT RESPONDER (IN ALL APPROPRIATE PPE) THE PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED IN THE U.P.S. DMP PROGRAM. 1 GAL INNER CONTAINER WAS DISPOSED OF DUE TO A SLIGHT LEAK SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED (THROUGH THE D.I.R) OF A LOOSE CAP TO AVOID FUTURE INCIDENTS SUCH AS THIS.

column168: AS TRANSFER LABORERS WERE UNLOADING TRUCKS, THEY NOTICED THIS BOX LEAKING. IT IS UNKNOWN AS TO WHAT CAUSED THIS FAILURE. THE TRANSFER LABORERS REPACKED THIS BOX. THEY ALSO DISINFECTED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL.

column42: REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR CLINICAL WASTE, UNSPECIFIED, N.O.S. OR (BIO) MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S., OR BIOMEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S.
column168: AS THE TRANSFER LABORERS WERE UNLOADING THE TRUCK THEY NOTICED THIS BOX LEAKING IT IS UNKNOWN WHAT CAUSED THIS FAILURE. THE TRANSFER LABORERS REPACKED THIS BOX. THEY ALSO DISINFECTED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER IN UNLOAD-DOOR 13 WEARING P.P.E, I FOUND A  5-PART FLAMMABLE LIQUID THAT WAS STAINED ON BOTTOM OF BOX. I CONSULTED DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID. I CONTAINED PACKAGE IN SPILL TUB AND REMOVED IT TO HAZMAT/ REWRAP AREA. INSPECTION SHOWED 4 OF 48 GLASS BOTTLES HAD BROKEN AND INNER BOXES HAD BEEN PACKAGED ON THEIR SIDE INSIDE OF OUTER BOX.. WASTE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP AND REMAINDER WAS REPACKED IN SALVAGE DRUM AND R.T.S.

column42: REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR CLINICAL WASTE, UNSPECIFIED, N.O.S. OR (BIO) MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S., OR BIOMEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S.
column168: WET AND LEAKING BOXES WERE DISCOVERED WHILE UNLOADING. THE BOXES WERE REPACKED AND PROCESSED. TRAILER WAS THEN WASHED OUT WITH DISINFECTANT. SALES CONTACTED GENERATOR ABOUT INCIDENT. SALES TO SET UP TRAINING SESSION FOR GENERATOR EMPLOYEES ON PROPER HANDLING AND PACKAGING OF BIOHAZARD WASTE.

COMPANY DRIVER IN YARD OBSERVED BIN LEAKING AND ADVISED MANAGEMENT. THE LEAK WAS STABILIZED BY MOVING ONTO PLASTIC AND REPAIRS MADE TO THE BOTTOM OF THE BIN. THE GROUND AREA THAT WAS CONTAMINATED AREA APPROX. 1 1/2 FT WAS DUG UP TO A DEPTH OF APPROX .5 INCHES AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL PLACED BACK IN THE BIN FOR DISPOSAL. NOTE: THE BIN WAS RED TAGGED TO PREVENT FUTURE USE UNTIL PROPER REPAIRS ARE MADE. ADDITIONAL: UPON LOADING THE BIN ONTO A TRUCK FOR DISPOSAL IT BEGAN TO LEAK AGAIN. AT THIS TIME THE BIN WAS MOVED ONTO CONCRETE SLAB NEXT TO SHOP WHERE MORE EXTENSIVE REPAIRS ARE BEING MADE TO INSURE IT DOESN'T LEAK IN TRANSIT.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN PRIMARY SORT.  ONE GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER WAS DROPPED AND THE CAP CRACKED.  THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: PASCHALL DRIVER HAD STOPPED AT A SCALEHOUSE AND WAS BEING INSPECTED BY THE OFFICER WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT HE HAD PRODUCT LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER.  ONE OF THE 55 GALLON DRUMS HAD A RIP IN THE SEAM ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  EMI CONTRACTED RED J ENVIRONMENTAL OUT OF ALBUQUERQUE, NM TO HANDLE THE SPILL CLEAN-UP.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL AREA CLEANED UP.  THE OVER PACK WAS PLACED BACK ON THE LOAD TO BE DELIVERED TO PTL'S EL PASO, TX. TERMINAL FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO LOS ANGELES, CA. PER THE SHIPPERS REQUEST.  THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS WIPED DOWN BY THE CLEAN-UP CREW AND IT WAS REQUESTED BY THE CLEAN-UP CREW THAT THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER BE WASHED TO ENSURE THE PRODUCT WAS TOTALLY GONE.  THIS WAS DONE AND THE PASCHALL DRIVER CONTINUED ON THE EL PASO, TX. TERMINAL TO LEAVE THE OVERPACK, THEN ON TO HIS DESTINATION POINT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: I OFF LOADED MY TRUCK FIRST AT MONTEBELLO. I THOUGHT IT WOULD BE ALRIGHT TO DRIVE THE TRUCK TO PARAMOUNT, LOADED WITH 4,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL. I WENT ON WEST ROSE CRAN, I PASTED THE TURN OFF, SO, I WENT FURTHER ON TO MAKE A U-TURN. I MADE A U-TURN, I WENT ON EAST ROSE CRANS.  I MADE A LEFT TURN, THE TURN WAS VERY SHARP AS, I WAS COMING TO THE TURN A TRUCK WAS STICKING-OUT IN MY WAY SO, I MADE MY TURN ALITTLE SHARPER, SO I CAN GET INTO THE STREET. AT THAT TIME I WAS LOOKING IN MY MIRROR TO MAKE SURE I DIDN'T GO ON TOP OF THE CURB. I JUST KNICKED THE CURB, AND SUDDENLY THE TRAILOR ROLLED-OVER TO THE SIDE. I STOPPED! I GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND CHECKED TO SEE IF THEIR WAS ANY LEAKS. THEIR NO LEAKS THEN I CALLED STACY! WHILE I WAS TALKING TO STACY. TO TELL HER WHAT HAPPENED, THE DIESEL STARTED LEAKING STACY CALLED 911. I RAN THE TRAILOR TO SEE WHERE THE LEAKS COMING FROM. IT'S COMING FROM THE BOTTOM PLUG. SO, I PUT MY FINGER INTO THE PLUG TO STOP THE LEAK. SUDDENLY, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED. THAT ASKED ME "WHAT AM I HAULING" I TOLD THEM I'M HAULING 4,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL. THEY TOLD ME TO GET AWAY. I TOLD THEM I COULDN'T BECAUSE I WAS STOPPING THE LEAK WITH MY FINGER SO, THEY PUT A WOODEN PLUG TO STOP THE LEAK AND SO I CAN MOVE OUT OF THE WAY. THEN THEY WERE TALKING ABOUT CUTTING THE TOOK AND CALLING A HAZMAT VACUUM TRUCK. I TOLD THEM I CAN PUMP OUT THE DIESEL INTO THE TRUCK SAFELY. THEY SAID "OK" I PUMPED IT INTO THE TRUCK, THEN THE TOW TRUCK CAME HE TURNED THE TRAILOR OVER. THE TOW TRUCK DISCONNECTED THE TRAILOR FROM THE TRUCK AND HAULED IT AWAY. THEN THE HAZMAT GUY TOLD ME THAT I CAN NOT LEAVE UNTIL I CLEAN-UP THE TEN GALLONS OF DIESEL. I CLEANED IT UP.

column168: PASCHALL DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE TO UNLOAD AND WHEN THE CONSIGNEE OPENED THE BACK DOORS OF THE TRAILER THEY NOTICED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER. THE CONSIGNEE PUT ON A MASK AND CRAWLED INTO THE TRAILER TO INVESTIGATE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT (1) OF THE 55-GALLON DRUMS, 5TH ROW FROM THE BACK WAS LEAKING FROM A SEAM IN THE BOTTOM OF THE BARREL. THE CONSIGNEE REMOVED THE LEAKING DRUM TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AND PLACED IT IN AN OVERPACK DRUM ALONG WITH ALL THE SPILL THEY CLEANED UP OFF THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE  LEAKING DRUM ALONG WITH THE REST OF THE LOAD WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE AND OUR DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO HIS NEXT PICK-UP.

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED ODOR EMANATING FROM & PRODUCT ON SIDES OF TANK CAR.  CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE SENT RESPONDERS FROM CHICAGO TO TOOL TIGHTENED MANWAY COVER BOLTS & CLEAN PRODUCT FROM SIDES OF CAR.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED CAR VENTING IN YARD.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND THE VAPOR VALVE WAS OPEN & PLUG MISSING.  RESPONDERS CLOSED THE VAPOR VALVE & APPLIED ANGLE VALVE PLUG, ELIMINATING VAPOR RELEASE.  TANK CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTER SECUREMENT COMPLETED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE BNSF TRAIN AWAITING RELIEF CREW ON MAIN TRACK, FRA INSPECTOR REPORTED FINDING A TANK CAR IN TRAIN THAT WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  TRAIN MET BY BNSF RESPONDERS AT LINCOLN, NE.  RESPONDERS FOUND PRODUCT DAMPNESS AT BOC.  BOC (BOTTOM OUTLET CAP) WAS FOUND TO BE 1/2 TURN LOOSE & IT WAS TOOL TIGHTENED.  PRODUCT DAMPNESS AT BOC WAS WIPED & NO FURTHER DAMPNESS NOTED AFTER BOC TOOL TIGHTENED.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

WE PRESENTED TRAILER FOR UNLOADING AND CUSTOMER SUPPLIED A HOSE FOR UNLOADING OF MATERIAL.  DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE CUSTOMER'S HOSE FAILED SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 12 GALLONS OF MATERIAL.  IT WAS CAUGHT IN THE CONTAINMENT PIT AND NEUTRALIZED BY THE CUSTOMER.  NO ONE WAS INJURED AND CUSTOMER THEN USED CARRIERS HOSE TO FINISH UNLOADING.  CUSTOMER IS ARRANGING FOR PROPER DISPOSAL OF SPILLED PRODUCT.

FOUR OF FOUR FILL HOLE COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE, GATX 11209, APRIL 8, 2001, DETROIT DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS, SUNDAY APRIL 8, 2001, AT RIVER ROUGE YARD IN RIVER ROUGE, MICHIGAN, CAR INSPECTOR FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 11209, CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM IT CORPORATION ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WERE FOUR OF FOUR FILL HOLE COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY IT CORPORATION WHO TIGHTENED THE FOUR FILL HOLE COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS. IT ALSO APPEARED THE FILL HOLE COVER WAS WARPED. AT APPROXIMATELY 11:45 P.M. THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED. CAUSE CODE 224 NARRI = 5(5+5+0)X(2+0)=100

column168: CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINING PLASTIC CONTAINERS OF ORGANOCHLORINE PESTICIDE WAS PUNCTURED WITH A FORKLIFT WHILE BEING MOVED AROUND THE DOCK.  THIS RESULTED IN THE SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 2.5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ON THE CONCRETE SURFACE.CF EMPLOYEES PUT OUT A CLAY BASED ABSORBENT AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS UNLOADING A DRUM OF HYDROBROMIC ACID, ETHLAMINE AND RAN A FORK INTO THE DRUM.  THE FORK ONLY PUTURED THE DRUM ALLOWING A RELEASE OF 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL QUICKLY CLEANED UP THE RELEASE WITH FLOOR DRY.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A 85 GALLON ALONG WITH ABORSBANT MATERIAL.

column62: Abrasion; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR LOADED UNIT WAS NORTH BOUND ON CARDINAL DRIVE IN BEAUMONT TEXAS.  OUR DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF HER UNIT GOING INTO A LEFT CURVE.  THE UNIT ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE SLID ON THE HIGHWAY PAVEMENT HIT A BRIDGE GUARD RAIL THEN FLIPPED OVER ONTO A GRASS EMBANKMENT AND SLID DOWN A 20 FOOT EMBANKMENT.  WHEN THE UNIT HIT THE GUARD RAIL IT PUNCTURED THE FUEL TANKS ON THE TRACTOR AND PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE CARGO TANK CAUSING 8 GALLON OF PROPYLENE OXIDE TO SPILL ON THE GRASS.  GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL

AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, APRIL 4, 2001, WHILE SWITCHING CARS GENERAL CHEMICAL ON #4 EAST ON THE CHESTER INDUSTRIAL TRACK IN MARCUS HOOK, PA, CREW YPSC32 NOTED PRODUCT VENTING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 6300 CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID, SPENT. CAUSE CODE 282 NARRI = 5(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

CASEY ALSO RESPONDED TO FIND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED (OPEN APPROX. 3/8") AND THE BOTTOM OPERATING HANDLE WAS NOT PINNED. THE CAP WAS INSTALLED WRENCH TIGHT AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVING.  THE CAR WAS STENCILED ON EACH SIDE; "LEAKING T/C, DO NOT LOAD, BAD BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE". THE LUMBERTON, NC FIRE DEPARTMENT OBSERVED WETNESS ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR ETCX 29123.  THEY REPORTED THIS TO CSXT THROUGH THE 24-HOUR EMERGENCY COMMUNICATIONS CENTER.  THE LEAK WAS VERY SLIGHT WITH THE PRODUCT COMING FROM AN UNIDENTIFIED SOURCE AT THE TOP OF THE CAR AND RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE AND DRIPPING, TWO OR THREE DROPS A MINUTE. column168: DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS, LIQUID PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE FILL-HOLE OF TANK CAR CGTX 70579.  A RAILROAD EMPLOYEE WAS STANDING ADJACENT TO THE TANK CAR WHEN THE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS SPLASHED WITH SULFURIC ACID ON HIS HAT, COAT, AND GLOVES.  THE EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY REMOVED THE CONTAMINATED CLOTHING AND WENT TO THE YARD OFFICE TO WASH ANY REMAINING PRODUCT OFF HIS BODY.  THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT EXPERIENCE ANY SIGNIFICANT INJURIES AND RETURNED TO WORK THE NEXT DAY.  AN AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES FIELD INSPECTOR AND THE SHIPPER WERE CALLED TO INSPECT AND MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO SECURE THE CAR.  UPON INSPECTING THE CAR IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FILL-HOLE GASKET WAS DAMAGED AND UNABLE TO SEAL THE CLOSURE AT THE FILL-HOLE LID.  A NEW GASKET WAS FORMED FROM TEFLON ROPE AND PLACED ON THE FILL-HOLE OPENING.  THE FILL-HOLE LID WAS RE-SECURED AND THE CAR WAS MOVED BACK AND FORTH TO ENSURE THAT THE FILL-HOLE LID WAS LIQUID TIGHT.  NO FURTHER LEAKS WERE DETECTED.  THE CAR BODY AND FITTINGS WERE CLEANED WITH WATER AND SODA ASH.  ONCE THE CAR WAS CLEANED IT WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NARRI:  (5(5+5+0) X (2+2)=200  CAUSE CODE= 234

column168: ON 04/14/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 0100 HOURS, WHILE SWITCHING IN THE CN/IC "A" YARD, HOMEWOOD, IL, TWO CN/C TRAIN CREW MEMBERS REPORTED THAT THEY WERE EXPOSED TO VAPORS COMING FROM RAIL TANK CAR ACFX 79162, SPENT SULPHURIC ACID.  BOTH EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL, EXAMINED AND RELEASED BACK TO FULL DUTY.  TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED. CN/IC HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND FOUND TWO BOLTS ON THE FILL HOLE COVER WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT AND THE GASKET MISALIGNED WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  GASKET WAS PROPERLY POSITIONED AND FILL HOLE COVER BOLTS TOOL TIGHTENED BY THE TEAM.  TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column168: ON 04/05/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 1715 HOURS, WHILE CONDUCTING A YARD INSPECTION AT THE CN/IC DESTREHAN YARD, A CN/IC CARMAN NOTED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY AREA OF RAIL TANK CAR SCMX 2657.  TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  CN/IC RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THREE OF SIX MANWAY EYEBOLTS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.  EYEBOLTS PROPERLY SECURED BY THE TEAM AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE TEAM ALSO NOTED THAT THE AIR VALVE PLUG WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT.  PLUG PROPERLY SECURED BY THE TEAM.  TANK CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE ON THE DOCK, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THREE DAMAGED, TEN POUND PLASTIC BAGS. APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE BAGS WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION,  A DUSTPAN AND A BROOM. THE DAMAGED BAGS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A TWENTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED. +

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING, 55 GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE THIRD QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE LEAK TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BREATHER CAP.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A BLUE HAZMAT BAG AND THEN INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE BREATHER CAP WAS TIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING DRUM AND WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE ON THE DOCK, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DETECTED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE TRAILER, ONE LEAKING, 55 GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP  USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PATCHED WITH PUTTY AND PLACED INTO A 85 GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM.  THE DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, 25 POUND PLASTIC BAG WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FIRST QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF A CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE BAG WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, A BROOM AND DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED BAG WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK BAG. THE BAG WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED 50 POUND PLASTIC BAGS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 3 POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED WHEN THE PACKAGING FAILED DUE TO LOOSE SEALS. THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A DUSTPAN AND A BROOM.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT AND THE 2 DAMAGED BAGS WERE PLACED INTO A 50 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION AT THE TERMINAL. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT CONTINUED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, 55 GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED THE SURROUNDING DUNNAGE.  THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENTS AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT AND AFFECTED DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO A 30 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO 65 GALLON OVERPACK DRUM AND WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE QUART METAL CANS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FIRST QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER. DRIVER WAS HEADING NORTH ON RTE 495 IN HAVERHILL MA, NOTICED SOMETHING DRIPPING FROM REAR CORNER OF TRAILER, PULLED INTO REST AREA BEFORE EXIT 52. HE OPENED TRAILER DOOR AND VAPOR CAME OUT. HE CALLED DISPATCH AND CHEMTRAC & PCI (SHIPPER) FOR INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO HANDLE SITUATION. STATE TROOPER PULLED INTO REST AREA, DRIVER EXPLAINED SITUATION AND TROOPER CLOSED REST AREA AND CALLED HAVERHILL FIRE DEPT. ONCE FIRE DEPT ARRIVED THEY WERE UNSURE OF WHAT TO DO. WE CALLED CLEAN HARBORS. BY THAT TIME SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE AND OUR SAFETY MANAGER ARRIVED, BUT WERE NOT ALLOWED BY FIRE DEPT. TO APPROACH VEHICLE. IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT DRIVER'S PALLET JACK BROKE LOOSE FROM LOAD BAR AND PUNCTURED DRUM THAT WAS SECURED SAFELY IN TRAILER. LOADBAR WAS REPLACED WITH NEW ONE.

AS REPORTED TO YOUR OFFICE, THERE WAS A SOLVENT SPILL THAT OCCURRED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY REFERENCED ABOVE.  ON THURSDAY APRIL 12, 2001, AT AROUND 8:00 P.M., APPROXIMATELY 275 GALLONS OF PETROLEUM NAPTHA ( 150 SOLVENT ) WERE SPILLED ONTO THE ASPHALT.  THE COAL CITY COB DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING THE SOLVENT.  DRIVER REALIZED THE HOSES WERE HOOKED TO THE GEAR PUMP REVERSE OF STANDARD POLICY.  WHEN DRIVER WENT TO SWITCH HOSES ON PUMP THE PRODUCT VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED PROPERLY.  AS SOON AS THE HOSES WERE DISCONNECTED MATERIAL GRAVITY FLOWED OUT OF HOSE ONTO CONCRETE.  ALL MATERIAL WAS PROPERLY CONTAINED AND NONE LEAKED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT OUTSIDE OF FACILITY.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  ON 4/16/01 - EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL CONSTRUCTION OF SAN ANT0NIO WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND AND ASSESS THE AREA WHICH SPILL OCCURRED.  AFTER ASSESSMENT FROM EAGLE CONSTRUCTION, THE T.N.R.C.C. WAS NOTIFIED AND AT THAT TIME THE DECISION WAS MADE TO REMOVE AREAS OF CRACKED ASPHALT AND TAKE SAMPLES OF THE SOIL BENEATH.  AFTER THIS HAS BEEN DONE A FULL REPORT TO THE T.N.R.C.C. WITH SUPPORTING SOIL SAMPLES AND DOCUMENTATION WILL BE ON FILE OF THE REMEDIATION DONE AT THE 5243 SINCLAIR ROAD.  ALL MATERIAL WILL BE COLLECTED, CONTANERIZED, LABELED, MANIFESTED AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO E.P.A. AND D.O.T. REQUIREMENTS.

column168: OUTBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED ODOR EMANATING FROM TANK CAR.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND RESIDUE PRODUCT WETNESS AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC) & THE BOC GASKET FAILING TO SEAL.  GASKET WAS REPLACED & TEFLON APPLIED TO THREADS.  BOC WAS TOOL TIGHTENED & PRODUCT AROUND CAP ASSEMBLY WIPED.  NO FURTHER PRODUCT WETNESS NOTED AFTER SECUREMENT COMPLETED.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION & SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT FOR FUTURE CORRECTIVE ACTION.

DURING PRODUCT TRANSFER FROM TANK CAR TO CARGO TANK TRUCKS AFTER CAR DERAILED WITH NO RELEASE, A TRANSFER HOSE DEVELOPED A SMALL LEAK THAT WENT UNNOTICED UNTIL A PRODUCT SHEEN DISCOVERED ON THE WATER IN A DRAINAGE DITCH THAT WAS PREVIOUSLY BOOMED OFF.  CONTRACT RESPONDERS VACUUMED PRODUCT FROM WATER & DRAINAGE DITCH PRIOR TO DISMANTLING RETENTION/CLEANING BOOM.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: TRAILER WAS OPENED AND CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAY PERSONNEL DISCOVERED HYDROCHLORIC ACID ON OTHER FLOOR OF TRAILER.  THE CONTENTS OF TRAILER WERE PACKAGED WRONG AND CARGO ABOVE THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID PACKAGE FELL CAUSING DAMAGE.  CONTRACTORS QUICKLY CLEANED UP THE RELEASE WITH FLOOR/DRY SODA ASH.  THE CONTAMINATED DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN A POLY DRUM PENDING DISPOSAL.
LID ON DRUM WAS LOOSE AND ALLOWED 3-4 OUNCES OF MATERIAL TO RUN DOWN SIDE OF DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE AND IS BEING HELD FOR OFF-SITE DISPOSAL.

ONE 55 LB. BAG OF LEAD PHOSPHITE DIBASIC WAS DISCOVERED RIPPED OPEN DURING OFF-LOADING.  CF PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE MATERIAL IN AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SCHEDULED IT FOR FINAL DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.  E.M.I. JOB#10347

FILL HOSE DEVELOPED A LEAK.  DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO SHUT OFF TANK AND THE SHUT OFF VALVE RUPTURED.  STATE POLICE WAS DRIVING BY AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO RETURN TO THE WAREHOUSE.  VEHICLE WAS PARKED IN LOT WITH SPILL PAN IN PLACE.  VENT VALVE WAS OPENED TO RELEASE PRESSURE. NOTFIELD CHEM-TEL- WAS TOLD IT WAS NOT NECESSARY TO NOTIFY FIRE DEPARTMENT. VEHICLE MOUNTED VESSEL WAS SENT OUTSIDE OF COMPANY FOR REPAIR.

TRAIN CONDUCTOR TOLD FUELER TO PUT 1500 GAL IN UP 0466.  SIGHT GLASSES WERE BLACK (NOT READABLE) AND GAUGE SHOWED ZERO ON RIGHT SIDE.  GAUGE ON LEFT SHOWED 1500 GAL.  CREW WANTED 3,000 GAL TO MAKE TRIP. FUELER ATTACHED NOZZLE, TURNED ON.  AT APPROX.  500 GAL. AUTO-NOZZLE SHUT OFF, BUT TANK HAD BACKPRESSURE, CAUSING FUEL TO OVERFLOW ONTO THE GROUND. SPILLED APPROX 100 GAL. FUELER IMMEDIATELY PLACED ABSORBENT PADS OVER THE AREA (BETWEEN TRACK 17 & 19, WEST END, RAIL YARD). SOAKED UP ALL POSSIBLE.  CALLED UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMM. CNTR. CALLED GARNER ENVIR. FOR CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL OF WASTE PADS. NO FUEL RAN INTO DITCHES OR WASTE WATER AREAS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER STATES THAT AUTO CUT IN FRONT OF TRUCK. TO AVOID HITTING AUTO DRIVER STEERED TO RIGHT OF CAR AHEAD. TRUCKS RIGHT STEERING TIRE CAUGHT SOFT GROUND OUTSIDE OF PAVED SHOULDER AND THEN STEERED OFF HIGHWAY AND DOWN EMBANKMENT INTO DITCH. WHEN TRUCK/TRAILER ENTERED DITCH, WHEELS DUG INTO SOFT EARTH AND TRUCK/TRAILER TURNED OVER ON PASSENGER SIDE. SMALL TREES ADJACENT TO DITCH IMPINGED INTO ROLLOVER PROTECTION AND BROKE OFF THE 3/4" AIR INLET PIPING WITHIN  THE ROLLOVER PROTECTION. AT THIS POINT THE CARGO MATERIAL BEGAN TO SLOWLY FLOW FROM BROKEN 3/4" PIPE. FLOW RATE WAS DIMINISHED DUE TO CARGO TANK NON-VENTING. THE LOUISIANA STATE HAZMAT OFFICIALS WERE ON SCENE FIRST. HAZMAT SPILL CONTRACTOR ON SCENE AFTER BEING NOTIFIED. SITUATION WAS ASSESSED AND LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE SPILL VOLUME WAS APPROXIMATELY 600 U.S. GAL.ON 042801 A COMPANY WIDE (5) HOUR SAFETY MEETING WILL BE CONDUCTED TO ADDRESS ALL SAFETY ISSUES RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT AS WELL AS ALL OTHER SAFETY ISSUES VITAL TO THE SAFETY TRANSPORT OF BULK HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SUGGEST TRAILER MANUFACTURES REVIEW THE USE OF NON-METALLIC PIPING .
ARRIVED AT SHELL TO UNLOAD WATCHING SITE GAUGE  & PRODUCT CAME OUT OF VENT, SHEET DOWN. SITE GAUGE WASN'T WORKING
COULD NOT DETERMINE HOW MUCH PRODUCT IN TANK AT END OF UNLOAD PRODUCT CAME OUT VENT NO SITE GAUGE CLEANED UP WITH WATER.
OPENING EXTERNAL VALVE TO GET SAMPLE WHEN PRODUCT SQUIRTED OUT CUSTOMER CLEANED UP WITH SQUEEGIE
OUT FITTING WHICH ATTACHES TO FILL LINE WAS LEAKING CHANGED FITTING & FINISHED UNLOADING

column168: DRIVER WENT LEFT OF CENTER AND STRUCK ONCOMING VEHICLE THEN PROCEEDED OFF ROAD, STRUCK A POLE, AND OVERTURNED.  DAMAGES TO THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE EXTENSIVE. THE DRIVER RECEIVED INJURIES SO SEVERE ( IMPACT, NOT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL), HE WAS PRONOUNCED DEAD AT THE SCENE BY THE CORONER. THE VEHICLE ONCE OVERTURNED IMPACTED A METAL CULVERT WHICH CAUSED EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO THE CARGO TANK ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED.  THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED IN A FIELD AND A SMALL AMOUNT ENTERED THE TILE WHICH LEAD TO SUGAR CREEK.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT FOAMED THE AREA AND A SPILL CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED TO ASSIST WITH REMEDIATION.  THE HOME ON THE PROPERTY WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED WAS EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTION DUE TO THE VAPORS.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE ILLINOIS EPA WAS NOTIFIED. THE INVESTIGATION CONTINUES IN REFERENCE TO THE ACCIDENT CAUSE.  WITNESSES FOLLOWING OUR VEHICLE CONFIRMED HE HAD STOPPED AT A RAILROAD CROSSING JUST PREVIOUS TO THE ACCIDENT IT WAS HIS NORMAL SCHEDULE AND HE WAS IN COMPLIANCE WITH THE HOURS OF SERVICE REQUIREMENTS FATIGUE IS NOT BELIEVED TO BE AN ISSUE.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON HWY 520 IN ORANGE COUNTY, FL; HIT A DUMP TRUCK THAT STOPPED TO TURN LEFT.  OUR VEHICLE WAS TOWED AWAY.  BOTH DRIVERS WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND RELEASED.  A 300 GALLON GASOLINE SPILL OCCURRED WHEN A DUMP TRUCK RAISED IT'S BODY TO UNLOAD DIRT WHICH RUPTURED OUR TRAILER.  THE DIRT WAS BEING UNLOADED TO BE USED TO DIKE ANY POSSIBLE SPILL.  CRAWFORD WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AS WELL AS SWS TO CLEAN UP SPILL.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: ON FRIDAY APRIL 6TH CLEAN HARBORS CHICAGO FIELD SERVICE OFFICE MOBILIZED A THREE-MAN CREW TO THE BNSF RAIL YARD IN EAST QUINCY, MISSOURI. THE CREW ARRIVED ON SITE AT 5:00 P.M. APPROXIMATELY AND MET WITH THE YARDMASTER. THE TRACK WAS LOCKED OUT AND THE CAR WAS INSPECTED. STAINING ON ONE SIDE OF THE CAR WAS OBSERVED. VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE AREA BENEATH THE CAR DID NO REVEAL ANY SIGNS OR SPILLED WASTE. A CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE TOP OF THE CAR INDICATED THAT THE MAN WAY AND 4" FLANGE NEXT TO THE MAN WAY  HAD LEAKED. THE MAN WAY WAS OPENED AND THE GASKET WAS INSPECTED. THE GASKET WAS PINCHED AND DAMAGED. THE 4" FLANGE WAS OPENED AND THE GASKET WAS INSPECTED. NO VISUAL DAMAGE TO THE GASKET WAS OBSERVED. NEW GASKET WERE FABRICATED AND THE FLANGE AND LID WERE REPLACED. THE SIDE OF THE RAILCAR WAS CLEANED AND THE CREW DEMOBILIZED AT APPROXIMATELY 11:30 P.M.

NATX26801 REPORTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN BIRMINGHAM, AL. THE CAR WAS LEAKING A STEADY STREAM FROM ONE OF THE 2" INTERNAL HEATER COIL PIPES. TERMINAL PERSONNEL TIED A BUCKET OVER THE LEAKING PIPE AND MOVED THE CAR TO ISOLATE IT. CSXT DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO STOP THE LEAK AND CONDUCT ANY CLEANUP. THE CONTRACTOR CONFIRMED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM AROUND THE CAP ON THE INTERNAL HEATER COIL PIPE. THEY TIGHTENED THE CAP AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE SHIPPER WILL OBTAIN AN FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY TO MOVE THE CAR BACK TO THEIR FACILITY FOR UNLOADING. NARRI: 5(5+1+0)X(2+)=60 CAUSE CODE: 631

Y30527 WAS DELIVERING Q60126'S CUT TO THE UP RR WHEN IT WENT INTO EMERGENCY AT THE SOUTH END OF CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN NEW ORLEANS, LA. INSPECTION FOUND 2 CAR DERAILED. DOWX 79571'S LEAD SET OF WHEELS CLIMBED THE SWITCH AND DERAILED ONCE THE CAR CLEARED THE SWITCH. AS THE CAR WAS PULLED DOWN THE TRACK THE CAR PASSED OVER THE NOPB SWITCH AND THE SET OF WHEELS MOVED UNDER THE CAR AND BROKE OFF THE HEATER PIPES AND THE 2" AUXILIARY VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. IT ALSO CAUSED THE REAR SET OF WHEELS TO BE DERAILED. BOTH SETS OF TRUCK WERE OUT FROM UNDER THE CAR AND IT CAME TO REST SUSPENDED IN THE AIR, HELD IN PLACE BY THE COUPLERS OF THE CAR ON BOTH SIDES. THE SECOND CAR, DOWX8318 HAD ONE WHEEL DERAILED. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER, WR GLEASON RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT WHEN THE AUXILIARY VALVE WAS TORN OFF, APPROXIMATELY 1 CUP OF PRODUCT THAT WAS ENTRAINED IN THE PIPE WAS RELEASED. THE CREW OF TRAIN Q27224 WAS SWITCHING CARS IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S OAK YARD IN DETROIT, MI, WHEN THEY DETECTED AN ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR ACFX 83765. THEY NOTIFIED THE YARD MASTER AND SET THE CAR OUT OF THEIR TRAIN. TRAINMASTER WILSON AND A MECHANICAL CAR INSPECTOR CHECKED OUT THE CAR BUT FOUND SOURCE OF LEAKAGE, NOR COULD THEY DETECT ANY ODOR. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND APPROVED CSXT TO CALL AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO INSPECT THE CAR. THE CONTRACTOR DID NOT DETECT ANY ODORS BUT HE FOUND THAT THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE OPERATING ROD FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV) WAS LOOSE. HE TIGHTENED THE NUT 1 1/2 TURNS.THE CONTRACTOR ALSO FOUND THAT ONE OF THE MANWAY SECUREMENT SWING BOLTS WAS STRIPPED AND THE NUT COULD NO BE MADE WRENCH TIGHT. THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE PROBLEM AND ARRANGED FOR A MOBIL RAIL CAR REPAIR CO. TO REPLACE THE BOLT. NARRI: 2(4+1+0)X2+0=20 CAUSE CODE: 533

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment; Rollover Accident
column168: CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TRAIN Q40124 DERAILED 26 CARS IN A GENERAL PILE UP JUST EAST OF POINT OF ROCK, MD, AT MILEPOST BA 41.8. THERE WERE TWO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TANK CARS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT, GATX 60254, LOAD MOLTEN SULFUR, AND UCLX 16074, LOAD OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE. CSXT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CARR TO DETERMINE IF THERE WAS PRODUCT RELEASE. FOLLOWING A SEVERAL HOUR DELAY WHILE THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCY CONDUCTED HELICOPTER FLY OVERS TO IDENTIFY THE CARS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT. CSXT'S CONTRACTOR AND THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT CONDUCTED A WALKING INSPECTION OF THE CARS. THEY FOUND THE GATX 60254 WAS ROLLED OVER ON THE GROUND WITH THE MANWAY COVER IN THE DIRT AND THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THIS CAR UCLX 16074 WAS DERAILED WITH THE TANK ON THE GROUND, LEANING AT THE 11:00 POSITION. THIS CAR HAD A SMALL DRIP (1 DROP EVERY 30SECS) FROM THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE OPERATION ROD FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE 2" AUXILIARY VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS PULLED OUT OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE'S PIPE EXTENSION BELL CAP, BUT THERE WAS NO RELEASE FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. BOTH CARS WERE SIGNIFICANTLY DAMAGED AND THE PRODUCT MUST BE TRANSFERRED. THE CARS WERE RERAILED AND WILL BE MOVED TO CSXT'S RAIL YARD FOR TRANSFER.

column168: THE DELIVERING CARRIER (CSXT) WAS CONTACTED BY CHEMTREC CONCERNING A CALL RECEIVED FROM THE CAR SHIPPER. THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE AND THE CONSIGNEE HAD FOUND THAT THE TANK CAR WAS VENTING PRODUCT VAPOR FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. THE CONSIGNEE CHECKED THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR AND FOUND IT TO BE 35 P.S.I. AS THE PRESSURE WAS WELL BELOW THE PRV ACTUATION PRESSURE, THE CONSIGNEE DETERMINED THAT THE PRV WAS MALFUNCTIONING. THE CONSIGNEE APPLIED A "CHLORINE C KIT" CAP TO THE PRV WHICH SUBSTANTIALLY REDUCED THE VAPOR BEING EMITTED FROM THE CAR. THE SHIPPER HAD CONTACTED CHEMTREC IN AN ATTEMPT TO LOCATE A "MIDLAND" CAPPING KIT WHICH COULD BE USED ON THIS PARTICULAR CAR CHEMTREC CONTACTED CSXT AND CSXT CONFERRED WITH THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE. CSXT PROVIDED THE NAME OF AND OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR (HEAPCO) THAT HAD A "MIDLAND KIT" AND COULD APPLY SAME TO LEAKING CAR. THE CONTRACTOR, HEPACO, RESPONDED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY AND APPLIED PART OF THE MIDLAND KIT TO FULLY SEAL AND SECURE THE LEAK FROM THE PRV. THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY FOR OFF LOADING. *NOTE: THE DELIVERING CARRIER (CSXT) IS MAKING THIS REPORT AS REQUIRED BY 49 CFR PART 171.6 AS THE CARRIER HAS KNOWLEDGE THAT THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. THE RAILCAR WAS NOT IN CSXT'S POSSESSION NOR WAS CSXT RESPONSIBLE FOR THE RELEASE THAT OCCURRED. NARRI=2(5+10) X(2+0)=60 CAUSE CODE= 417

04/09 CSXT REQUESTED MILLENNIUM TO RESPOND TO A LEAKING TANK CAR AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S MILLDALE YD (BUFFALO & 50TH ST) IN JACKSONVILLE, FL. GATX 87205, LD TURPENTINE, WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHILE SITTING STILL. MR NATE SHERMAN, MILLENNIUM RESPONDED & FOUND THE CAR WAS LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON TOP OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ACCOUNT THE CAR WAS OVERFILLED. THE PRODUCT FLOWED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR & WAS DRIPPING ON THE GROUND. SORBENT PADS WERE PLACED UNDER THE DRIP TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. MILLENNIUM ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING GLAND NUT BUT IT WAS ALREADY TIGHT. THEY ATTEMPTED TO DRAIN SOME PRODUCT OFF FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BUT COULD NOT BECAUSE THE LINE WAS PLUGGED. THEY CONNECTED A HOSE TO THE LIQUID VALVE & VENTED EXCESS PRESSURE INTO A 55 GAL DRUM & COLLECTED 1-2 GALS OF PRODUCT. THE LEAK STOPPED. PACKING MATERIAL WAS STUFFED AROUND THE OPERATING ROD & THE SORBENTS PLACED IN THE CAP. CSXT THEN MOVED THE CAR A SHORT DISTANCE INTO THE MILLENNIUM PLANT FOR OFFLOADING. column168: THE DRIVER HAD FINISHED HIS ROUTE AND RETURNED TO HIS FACILITY WHERE HE BEGAN TO UNLOAD HIS TRUCK.  IN THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK, HE DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD FALLEN OVER AND THE LID OF THE POLY DRUM CRACKED. APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF THE SOLVENT LEAKED OUT OF THE LID AND INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  ALL THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE BACK AND IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL WHICH WAS CONTAINERIZED. THE CRACKED LID WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW ONE. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY THREE POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 50A BRIGHAM IN MARLBOROUGH, MA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM SECUREMENT PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: THEY WERE LOADING A SHIPMENT OF PALLETIZED DRUMS OF SOLVENT WASTE INTO A TRAILER.  THE FORKLIFT THAT WAS CARRYING THE PALLET ONTO THE TRAILER HIT A BUMP AND TWO 30-GALLON DRUMS FELL OFF THE PALLET ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. APPROXIMATELY HALF A GALLON OF SOLVENT SPILLED OUT OF THE DRUMS.  ALL OF THE SPILLED SOLVENT WAS CONTAINED IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH AN ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED AS WASTE.  THE DRUMS WERE REPALLETIZED SECURED WITH SHRINK WRAP AND THE RINGS TO THE LIDS TIGHTENED DOWN. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 50A BRIGHAM IN MARLBOROUGH, MA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM SECUREMENT AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HIS TRUCK AT THE DESIGNATED FACILITY.  THEY WERE PLACING THE DRUMS ON A PALLET AND TAKING THEM AWAY BY FORKLIFT.  THE PARKING AREA, WERE THEY WERE UNLOADING THE TRUCK, HAS UNEVEN SURFACE CAUSING THE FORKLIFT TO BOUNCE.  ONE OF THE DRUMS ON THE PALLET FELL OFF AND THE IMPACT ON THE GROUND CAUSED A CRACK ON THE LID NEAR THE BUNG. ABOUT ONE QUART OF SOLVENT SPILLED ONTO THE ASPHALT LOT AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEAN UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CRACKED LID WAS REPLACED AND THE DRUM AND WASTE GENERATED WAS SENT FOR TREATMENT.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 5 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TREATED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY ON 10 ELEANOR DRIVE IN NEW KINGSTOWN, PA.  THE DRIVER AND THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WERE COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM SECUREMENT AND FORKLIFT HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.
SEAL ON PRODUCT OFF LOADING PUMP FAILED.

column168: PURSUANT TO 49 CFR S171.16, THE FOLLOWING IS A DETAILED DESCRIPTION OF THE SUBSEQUENT ACTIONS TAKEN UPON THE DISCOVERY OF TWO LEAKING PACKAGES CONTAINING WASTE MATERIAL. THE PACKAGES WERE IN TRANSIT FROM THE GENERATORS FACILITY TO OUR RCRA PERMITTED DISPOSAL FACILITY. ON APRIL 24,2001, THE INITIAL TRANSPORTER TRIAD, INC., TRAILER#: 3112 WAS STAGED AT THE RECEIVING BAYS (SEE ATTACHED FACILITY DIAGRAM) OF ENSCO WEST INC, 1737 EAST DENNI ST., WILMINGTON, CA 90744. ENSCO WEST, INC. (EWI), IS FULLY PERMITTED TREATMENT, STORAGE AND DISPOSAL FACILITY WHO'S DBA FOR TRANSPORTATION IS DIVISION TRANSPORT, INC. THE FOLLOWING WASTE TRANSPORTED ON MANIFEST#; AR1190687, WAS RELINQUISHED TO ENSCO WEST, INC FOR CONSOLIDATION WITH OTHER HAZARDOUS WASTE LOADS, WHICH WILL BE SHIPPED TO OUR INCINERATION FACILITY IN EL DORADO, ARKANSAS. EWI SUBSEQUENTLY SIGNED OFF ON THE  MANIFEST AS THE SECONDARY TRANSPORTER, TAKING POSSESSION OF THE WASTE, AND PROCEEDED TO OFF-LOAD THE PACKAGES. UPON ENTERING THE TRAILER, IT WAS NOTICED BY ONE OF THE WAREHOUSE OPERATORS THAT TWO CUBIC YARD SACKS APPARENTLY LEAKED MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR'S LINER (SEE MANIFEST AND PICTURE ENCLOSED). ONE SACK HAD SMALL HOLES NEAR ITS BASE AND THE OTHER WAS MOUNTED TO ITS PALLET ON ITS SIDE, CAUSING LIQUID TO SPILL FROM THE OPENING OF THE INNER LINING. THE OPERATIONS MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED AND INSTRUCTED THE WAREHOUSE OPERATOR TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND REPACKAGE THE CUBIC YARD SACKS. THE WAREHOUSE OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY DONNED THE PROPER LEVEL OF PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND PROCEEDED TO REPACKAGE THE TWO SACKS. THE LINER OF THE TRAILER WAS WIPED CLEAN OF THE SPILLED MATERIALS AND ALL SPILL RESPONSE MEDIA WAS DISPOSED OF AS WASTE. APPROXIMATELY 10-12 OUNCES OF MATERIAL SPILLED FROM THE TWO BAGS ONTO THE TRAILER'S FLOOR LINER. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TWO SACKS LEAKED DURING TRANSIT TO OUR DISPOSAL FACILITY.  BASED ON THE INTEGRITY OF THE PACKAGES AND THE FACT THAT ONE PACKAGE WAS MOUNTED IMPROPERLY TO ITS PALLET (SEE PICTURE), ENSCO WEST, INC. WILL RECOMMEND TO TRIAD TRANSPORT INC., THE INITIAL TRANSPORTER, TO TRAIN THEIR DRIVER ON THE PROCESS OF INSPECTING CONTAINERS FOR DEFICIENCIES PRIOR TO ALLOWING THEM TO BE LOADED ONTO THEIR TRAILERS.

THE TWO RAIL CARS FOR THE ABOVE NOTED SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT WASTE CONTROL SPECIALISTS IN ANDREWS, TEXAS WHEN A SMALL PIN HOLE LEAK WAS IDENTIFIED. A BLACK LIQUID WAS DRIPPING OUT. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF K169 AND K170 CODED MATERIAL WAS RELEASED. THE RAIL CARS WERE MOVED TO A CONTAINMENT AREA AND ANY RELEASED MATERIAL WAS REMEDIATED. IT APPEARS THAT OVER TIME A SEAM IN THE RAIL CARS DEVELOPED A SMALL HOLE DUE TO METAL FATIGUE. THIS COULD BE REMEDIED BY REPAIRING AND RESEALING THE SEAM.

THE TWO RAIL CARS FOR THE ABOVE NOTED SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT WASTE CONTROL SPECIALISTS IN ANDREWS, TEXAS WHEN A SMALL PIN HOLE LEAK WAS IDENTIFIED. A BLACK LIQUID WAS DRIPPING OUT. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF K169 AND K170 CODED MATERIAL WAS RELEASED. THE RAIL CARS WERE MOVED TO A CONTAINMENT AREA AND ANY RELEASED MATERIAL WAS REMEDIATED. IT APPEARS THAT OVER TIME A SEAM IN THE RAIL CARS DEVELOPED A SMALL HOLE DUE TO METAL FATIGUE. THIS COULD BE REMEDIED BY REPAIRING AND RESEALING THE SEAM.

CAR STOPPED IN FRONT OF OUR DRIVER AND HE HAD TO STOP IMMEDIATELY WHICH CAUSED HIS LOAD TO SHIFT TO THE NOSE. FOUR DRUMS ON THE FLOOR IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER WERE CRUSHED BY THE OTHER PRODUCTS ON PALLETS AND TOTES. A BOARD FROM A PALLET PUNCTURED ONE DRUM CAUSING THE SPILL.

ALL INCIDENTS ARE REVIEWED BY PETRO'S SAFETY COMMITTEE.  IDEAS ARE FORMULATED AND IMPLEMENTED TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF FUTURE INCIDENTS. DRIVER GOING IN STRAIGHT LINE FROM 17TH AVE.  WHEN DRIVE SHAFT SNAPPED BEHIND MAIN BEARING UNDER TRUCK, HITTING DELIVERY PIPE, PUNCTURING AND CAUSING HOLE-APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS FLOWED OUT OF PIPE ONTO ROADWAY AND INTO NEARBY CATCH BASIN.  MILRO CALLED BAYSIDE CREW CALLED, BOTH CLEANED UP ROADWAY AND CATCH BASIN.

column168: WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT, DOCKWORKER FOUND ONE BOX FROM THIS SHIPMENT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR SLIGHTLY LEAKING.  THE PICKUP DRIVER HAD PLACED A PALLET INBETWEEN TWO PALLETS TO SECURE THIS SHIPMENT, BUT THERE STILL WAS ENOUGH SPACE TO ALLOW THIS ONE BOX TO DISLODGE AND FALL TO THE FLOOR SUBSEQUENTLY CRUSHING ONE CAN IN IT, SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND PUT IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER AWAITING DISPOSITION.

WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT, DOCKWORKER FOUND SAID PALLET OF BOXES THAT HAD A FEW BOXES SLIGHTLY WET.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, ONE BOTTLE INSIDE ONE OF THE BOXES WAS FOUND BROKEN.  THIS WAS CAUSED BY NOT PROPERLY BRACING THE FREIGHT STAGED NEXT TO IT IN THE TRAILER.  APPARENTLY, THE FREIGHT NEXT TO IT SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT AND THE PRESSURE OF THE OTHER FREIGHT CAUSED SAID BOTTLE TO RUPTURE.  DAMAGED MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO SALVAGE CONTAINER AND ENTIRE SHIPMENT OF SAID PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

DOCKWORKER MOVED PALLET THAT DRUMS WERE TEMPORARILY BEING STAGED ON.  WHEN HE MOVED IT ONE OF THE DRUMS SLID OFF AND STRUCK AN EMPTY PALLET THAT WAS LAYING NEXT TO IT SUBSEQUENTLY PUNCTURING IT.  REPAIR PUTTY WAS PLACED OVER SMALL HOLE, SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.

FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS COMING INTO TRAILER TO REMOVE THE PALLET THAT THESE 3 DRUMS WERE ON.  RIGHT WHEN WAS JUST ABOUT TO PLACE THE FORKBLADES INTO THE PALLET THE TRAILER SUSPENSION BOUNCED A LITTLE CAUSING ONE OF THE FORKBLADES TO JUMP UP OVER THE PALLET SUBSEQUENTLY STRIKING AND PUNCTURING ONE OF THE DRUMS.  DAMAGED DRUM AND CLEANUP ABSORBENT WERE PLACED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER AND ARE AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, THREE DAMAGED, FIFTY POUND PLASTIC BAGS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY A HALF CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE BAGS WAS DUE TO BEING STRUCK BY ADJACENT FREIGHT DURING TRANSIT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENT PADS, A BROOM AND A SHOVEL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE THREE DAMAGED BAGS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER OVERPACK DRUM WHICH WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, FOUR DAMAGED, FIVE GALLON METAL PAILS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENT PADS, AND AMPHOMAG.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE FOUR DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF A CLOSURE ON THE DRUM LOOSENING DURING TRANSIT. WHILE UNLOADING THE PRODUCT INTO THE STORAGE TANK THE HOSE BLEW.  THE PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE GROUND.  THE HOSE FAILED. (HUMAN ERROR)

THE PRODUCT WAS BEING TRANSFERRED FROM THE CARGO TANK TO THE STORAGE TANK. THE STORAGE TANK WAS FILLED TO CAPACITY.  THE UNLOADER INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO PUT THE BALANCE TO THE PRODUCT INTO THE TOTE.  THE DRIVER INSERTED THE HOSE INTO THE TOTE AND STARTED THE TRANSFER.  AS THE CARGO TANK STARTED TO EMPTY THE DRIVER WENT TO SHUT THE VALUE OFF.  AT THE SAME TIME THE HOSE FELL OUT OF THE TOTE, AIR AND PRODUCT MIST WENT ON THE TOTE AND FLOOR.  THE CONSIGNEE CLEANED OFF THE TOTE AND FLOOR.
EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT WHEN HOSE RUPTURED CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO BE LOST.  CLEANUP PERFORMED BY FIRST RESPONSE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: ON APRIL 7, 2001 THE FARMERS COOPERATIVE ELEVATOR OF OTTOSEN, IOWA HAD A PROPANE GAS RELEASE FORM THEIR BOBTAIL DELIVERY TRUCK THAT WAS PARKED JUST INSIDE THE OPEN DOOR OF A STEEL STORAGE BUILDING.  THE FARMERS COOPERATIVE ELEVATOR IS LOCATED AT 71 BRADY AVE, OTTOSEN, IOWA.  THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED ABOUT 8:39 P.M.  AND REPORTED TO THE OTTOSEN FIRE DEPARTMENT CHIEF.  HE CALLED 911 AT 8:44 P.M.  SEE ENCLOSED COPY OF THE 911 CALLS. THE HAZ-MAT TEAM FROM FORT DODGE, SHERIFF'S DEPUTIES AND THE OTTOSEN, BODE AND WEST BEND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE PAGED.  RESIDENTS IN THE PATH OF THE VAPOR AND SURROUNDING AREA WERE EVACUATED TO THE EDGE OF TOWN, APPROXIMATELY ONE MILE FROM TOWN.  THE WEATHER WAS CLEAR WITH 30-40 MPH WINDS DISPERSING THE VAPOR CLOUD.  AN ESTIMATED 730 GAL OF PROPANE WAS RELEASED BEFORE THE WAS BROUGHT UNDER CONTROL.  RON POWELL, THE MANAGER OF THE FARMERS COOP WAS ABLE TO REPORT THE RELEASE TO THE DNR APPROXIMATELY 10:15 P.M. ON APRIL 7, 2001.  AN EVALUATION AND DEBRIEFING BY THE HAZ-MAT TEAM AFTER THE RELEASE WAS UNDER CONTROL WAS CONDUCTED WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND COOPERATIVE PERSONNEL.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT RISING TEMPERATURES, THAT EVENING, RESULTED IN INCREASING PRESSURE IN THE HOSE, CAUSING THE HOSE TO RUPTURE IN A ABRASION AREA ON THE HOME.  A PENCIL SIZE HOLE IN THE HOSE WAS THE RESULT.

column168: ACFX 71850 WAS FOUND LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S C  YARD IN EAST CHICAGO, IN.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER RESPONDED.  INVESTIGATION FOUND THE CAR WAS SHELL FULL AND LEAKING FROM THE AREA BETWEEN THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE MANWAY PLATE DUE TO 3 BOLTS BEING LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, AND THE INTERNAL PRESSURE ON THE PRODUCT.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND 300 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE REMOVED FROM THE CAR. AT THAT TIME THE CAR WAS MOVED INTO TRANSFLO FOR FURTHER PRODUCT REMOVAL.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF PESTICIDE WAS RELEASED AS A RESULT OF APPARENT OVERFILLING OF THE 275 GALLON TOTE BY THE MANUFACTURER / SHIPPER.  THE TOTE WAS NOTED TO BE 1.5 INCHES OVER THE FILL LINE AND THE FILL PORT (RESIDUAL LIQUID WAS NOTED IN THE RECESS SURROUNDING THE FILL PORT DUE TO OVERFILL). IT IS SUSPECTED THAT THE TOTE CONTENTS EITHER RELEASED DUE TO A COMBINATION OF THE OVERFILL AND OVER THE ROAD TRANSPORT AND/OR THE TOTE WAS SURROUNDED TIGHTLY BY OTHER SHIPMENTS DURING TRANSIT AND THE PRESSURE EXERTED BY THE OTHER SHIPMENT(S) CAUSED THE OVERFILLED TOTE TO "BURP".  SOME OF THE LIQUID RELEASED HAD PARTIALLY RAN DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TOTE ITSELF.  HOWEVER, NO FREE LIQUIDS WERE NOTED ON THE SURFACE AREA SURROUNDING THE TOTE.  IT WAS NOTED THAT A SECOND TOTE TANK (UN31H2/Y/04/99/USA) (SNYDER IND. INC. LN 4462/2072) (LAST TESTED ON 04/1999) WAS ALSO OVERFILLED A HALF OF AN INCH OVER THE FILL LINE AND HISTORICAL SPILLAGE AROUND THE FILL PORT AND THE WALLS OF THE TOTE WERE ALSO NOTED (NO FREE LIQUIDS).

THE DRIVER WAS IN TRANSIT FROM A CUSTOMER SITE TO HIS FACILITY WHEN HE ARRIVED AT HIS FACILITY AND OPENED THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK. HE DISCOVERED TWO 55-GALLON STEEL DRUMS HAD LEAKED ONE QUART OF FLAMMABLE SOLVENT INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED. THE LEAK CAME FROM THE LIDS OF THE DRUMS WHICH WERE NOT PROPERLY TIGHTENED. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED. THE RINGS TO THE DRUMS WERE THEN TIGHTENED THE CORRECT TORQUE TO SECURE THE LIDS. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 5 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON,IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION  AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column42: ORGANIC PEROXIDE TYPE C, SOLID, TEMPERATURE CONTROLLED
column168: THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE NAC PORT ALLEN FACILITY THE MORNING OF 4/25/01 AND LOADED THE TRAILER WITH THE SHIPMENTS FOR THE DAY. HE LOADED THE PERKADOX 16 ON TOP OF THE DRUMS, CHOOSING NOT TO USE THE COOL BOX STORED IN THE TEMPERATURE CONTROL ROOM. HE LEFT FOR HIS ROUTE AT APPROXIMATELY 600AM. THE SECOND STOP WAS SEA SAFE INC, THIS IS WHERE THE PERKADOX 16 WAS TO BE DELIVERED. PER THE CUSTOMER, THEY REFUSED THE SHIPMENT OF PERKODOX 16 DUE TO THE TEMPERATURE OF THE PRODUCT. THE DRIVER TOOK THE PERKADOX 16 AND PIT IN A PLASTIC BAG AND SET IT IN THE TRACTOR. HE SET IT ON THE FLOOR ON THE PASSENGER SIDE. HE WENT TO A NEAR BY STORE AND PURCHASED SOME ICE TO PUT IN THE PLASTIC BAG WITH THE PERKODOX 16. HE PROCEEDED ON WITH HIS DELIVERIES, WHICH TOOK HIM TO BEAUMONT, TX.HE WAS DRIVING IN THE LEFT LANE OF SOUTHBOUND HWY 69 WHEN THE THREE BOXES OF PERKADOX 16 DECOMPOSED. HE ATTEMPTED TO ACTIVATE THE EMERGENCY BRAKE BUT COULD NOT LOCATE IT WITH THE FOG IN THE TRACTOR. AT THIS POINT HE EXITED THE TRACTOR THROUGH THE DRIVER SIDE DOOR AND LANDED IN THE GRASS MEDIAN SEPARATING THE LANES. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER CROSSED TO THE RIGHT WENT THROUGH A GRASS MEDIAN AREA AND CROSSED WEST CARDINAL DRIVE. IT STOPPED IN THE FRONT YARD OF 2615 WEST CARDINAL ROAD, AIRBORNE EXPRESS. ACTION TAKEN AT THE TIME: THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EMERGENCY VEHICLES WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL WITH CHEMICAL BURNS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REQUESTED AND WAS SENT AN MSDS FOR PERKADOX 16. BOB HOFFMAN, THE HEALTH SAFETY ENVIRONMENT AND QUALITY OFFICER FOR INTERPLASTIC CORPORATION WAS INFORMED OF THE ACCIDENT. A HAZARDOUS CLEAN UP CREW WAS BROUGHT IN TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL IN THE CAB OF THE VEHICLE. THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO A LOCAL SITE AFTER IT WAD DEEMED STABLE. ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS: ALL NAC LOCATIONS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO REVIEW THE EXISTING POLICY FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF TEMPERATURE CONTROLLED ORGANIC PEROXIDE. THE TESTING FOR THE EXISTING HM126 TRAINING PROGRAM WAS REVISED TO INCLUDE A QUESTION ON TEMPERATURE CONTROLLED ORGANIC PEROXIDE. WE ARE REVIEWING TRAINING MATERIAL FROM THE VENDOR AND WILL INCLUDE THIS IN THE FUTURE TRAINING PROGRAMS. THE DRIVER DID NOT USE THE EXISTING TEMPERATURE CONTROL STORAGE BOX; WE ARE LOOKING AT A SMALLER BOX THAT WOULD BE MORE CONVENIENT FOR SMALL SHIPMENTS. COMMUNICATION HAS BEEN SENT TO ALL NAC LOCATIONS HIGHLIGHTING THE CONTRIBUTING FACTORS TO THIS INCIDENT AND REINFORCING THAT THERE IS A PROCEDURE THAT MUST BE FOLLOWED.

column168: AT APPROX 4:10 AM ON 4/24/2001, OUR DRIVER HAD FINISHED LOADING GASOLINE PRODUCT AT THE RAD ENERGY TERMINAL AND WAS IN ROUTE TO MAKE A DELIVERY. AS HE WAS MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN OFF OF HAMPTON ROAD ( SAME ROAD AS TERMINAL) ONTO DALY BLVD., HE OVERTURNED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER. AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT GASOLINE PRODUCT BEGAN T LEAK FROM THREE(3) COMPARTMENTS OF THE TRAILER AND ENTERED NEARBY STORM SEWER DRAINS. THE DRIVER VACATED HIS VEHICLE UNINJURED AND PRECEDED TO THE TERMINAL TO NOTIFY PERSONNEL THAT HE HAD JUST OVERTURNED HIS VEHICLE AND THAT GASOLINE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING. IMMEDIATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO VARIOUS AGENCIES TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL AS A MATTER OF PRECAUTION AND TO BE EVALUATED FOR ANY INJURIES. A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND BEGAN TO EFFECTUATE SPILL CONTAINMENT AND RECOVERY ALONG WITH LOCAL ATTENDING FIRED DEPARMENTS. THE VEHICLE WAS OFF-LOADED OF PRODUCT AND FINALLY UP-RIGHTED. CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS WERE INITIATED AND ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL REMOVED. THE CONTRACTOR AND THE COMPANY WORKED WITH ALL ATTENDING AGENCIES TO HAVE THIS MATTER PROPERLY HANDLED AND MITIGATED.

RESPONDED TO THE SPILL FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE FOR PROCESSING CONTAINED, SOLIDIFIED AND PROCESSED THE MATERIAL PLACED IN BAG FOLLOWING UPS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES I WORE THE PROPER P.P.E DROPPED PACKAGE CAUSED LEAKAGE PRELOAD MANAGER SHOULD REVIEW PACKAGE HANDLING RULES.

column168: TRAIN DERAILED ON MAIN TRACK AFTER TRAVERSING A VERTICAL SPLIT HEAD BROKEN RAIL.  SIX TANK CARS OF FUEL OIL OVERTURNED DOWN AN EMBANKMENT, COMING TO REST IN A CEDAR CREEK TRIBUTARY.  FOUR OF THESE TANK CARS RELEASED PRODUCT. ATSF 98645 SUSTAINED A 4 FOOT BY 11/2 FOOT HOLE TO THE LEFT SIDE OF TANK SHELL TO THE RIGHT OF THE REPORTING MARKS CAUSED BY IMPACT FROM OTHER DERAILING EQUIPMENT & SUBSEQUENT RELEASE OF PRODUCT IN THE CEDAR CREEK TRIBUTARY.  BN 974029 ON ITS SIDE HAD PRODUCT RELEASE VIA THE MANWAY COVER DUE TO LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WHICH WERE TIGHTENED AT DERAILMENT SITE. ATSF 98721 ALSO ON ITS SIDE WITH TOP VALVES AT NINE O'CLOCK POSITION HAD PRODUCT RELEASE VIA MANWAY DUE TO LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLTS, AS WELL AS A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE (VRV). BN 875091 ALSO ON ITS SIDE HAD PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV) OPERATING ROD AREA DUE TO A LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT AND VIA MANWAY DUE TO LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLTS.  ALL SECUREMENT ISSUES CORRECTED AT THE DERAILMENT SITE.  A DAM WAS BUILT TO KEEP PRODUCT FROM ENTERING CEDAR CREEK, THUS POOLING AROUND DERAILED EQUIPMENT IN THIS DRAINAGE DITCH.  REMAINING PRODUCT IN DAMAGED TANK CARS TRANSFERRED INTO OTHER TANK CARS.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS VACUUMED FROM DRAINAGE DITCH & ALL IMPACTED SOIL REMEDIATED.

column168: DRIVE FELL ASLEEP AS HE WAS APPROACHING TOLL BOOTH ENTRANCE.  AWOKE TO FINE HIMSELF IN TROUBLE, TRIED TO CORRECT PROBLEM, ONLY TO END UP IN A ROLLOVER CAME TO REST ON LEFT SIDE OF TRACTOR-TRAILER AGAINST CONCRETE MEDIAN DIVIDER EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO TRACTOR AND TRAILER TOTAL LOSS OF PRODUCT. SERIOUS INJURIES TO BOTH DRIVER AND CO-DRIVER BOTH TAKEN TO EMERGENCY CENTER.  EMERGENCY PERSONNEL, CORPORATE SAFETY DIRECTOR AND TERMINAL MANAGER WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY.  ALL DAMAGED EQUIPMENT WAS TOWED OFF SITE TO TERMINALS AND REPAIR FACILITIES LOCATION CLEAN-UP WAS PERFORMED. ACCIDENT WILL BE THE SUBJECT OF DISCUSSION AT FUTURE SAFETY MEETINGS. THIS ACCIDENT DID NOT RESULT IN A SPILL OF ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, EXCEPT FOR A SMALL AMOUNT OF TRACTOR DIESEL FUEL.  THIS DIESEL WAS CONTAINED AND DISPOSED OF BY THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL.  THE LIQUID HELIUM CONTAINER WAS DAMAGED IN THIS ACCIDENT.  THE INSULATED OUTER SHELL OF THE CONTAINER WAS TORN AND ALLOWED THE  VACUUM, THE TEMPERATURE OF THE LIQUID HELIUM WAS RISING AN PRESSURE WAS STARTING TO BUILD. IT THEN WAS DECIDED TO ALLOW THE LIQUID HELIUM TO BE VENTED TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT.  AND PRAXAIR PERSONNEL MADE THIS DECISION.  THE HELIUM WAS SAFELY VENTED TO THE ATMOSPHERE UNTIL THE INNER VESSEL PRESSURE WAS REDUCED TO ZERO.  THIS ACTION RESULTED IN A 100% LOSS OF THE TOTAL LIQUID HELIUM SHIPMENT.  THE DAMAGED TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS THEN SET UPRIGHT USING AIRBAGS  AND TOW TRUCK WINCH LINES.  ALL DAMAGED EQUIPMENT WAS REMOVED FROM THE ROADWAY AND CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED.  THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS THEN TAKEN TO A JACK B. KELLEY, INC.  TERMINAL FOR EVALUATION AND REPAIRS.

MATERIAL WAS FOUND LEAKING ON THE DOCK.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND A CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN FOR PROPER CLEAN UP AND DECONAMINATION.  ALL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM FOR PROPER HANDLING.

SPILL WAS CAUSED WHEN DRIVER WAS TRANSFERRING FUEL FROM ONE TANKER TO ANOTHER.  WHILE TRANSFERRING THE FUEL A CLAMP VIBRATED LOOSE CAUSING 20-30 GALLON SPILL ON THE SURFACE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE SYSTEM DOWN AND SPREAD SORBENT MATERIAL ON THE IMPACTED AREA.  OUR TERMINAL MANAGER WAS NOT AT THE TERMINAL AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL, HE WAS NOT NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL UNTIL TWO DAYS LATER.  WHEN OUR TERMINAL MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL, HE THEN MADE A SPILL REPORT TO THE CORPORATE OFFICE.  BUT THE REPORT WAS NOT CALLED IN UNTIL MAY. PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED TO CLEAN UP PRODUCT. THIS WAS NOT REPORTED ON THE TIME DUE TO TERMINAL MANAGER NOT BEING NOTIFIED WHEN THIS HAPPENED, AND WHEN HE WAS NOTIFIED HE DID NOT REPORT IT IMMEDIATELY TO CORPORATE SAFETY DEPARTMENT.

ON MONDAY, 4/16/01, AT ABOUT 1300 HOURS TANK CAR LOCATED AT THE AVONDALE YARD WAS FOUND BY UNION PACIFIC MECHANICAL FORCES TO BE RELEASING A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND UPRR SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TOBY TREVETT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  ADDITIONAL NOTIFICATION WERE MADE VIA THE UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER TO THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY, JEFFERSON PARISH HAZ/MAT, BRIDGE CITY FIRE DEPT. AND UNION CARBIDE THE SHIPPER. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE AIR VALVE AND LIQUID VALVE WERE OPEN.  IN ADDITION ALL EIGHT OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE BOLTS WERE LOOSE.  THE VALVES WERE CLOSED AND THE BOLTS SECURED.  THIS STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

WHILE PERFORMING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE OF CITX 33371.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO OBTAIN INFORMATION CONCERNING PROPER O-RINGS TO BE USED IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  THE PRESSURE WAS ALSO CHECKED ON THE CAR AND DETERMINED TO BE LESS THAN 50 PSI.  AFTER DETERMINING THE CORRECT MATERIAL TO USE, THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WAS DISSEMBLED, NEW O-RINGS INSTALLED, AND THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE REASSEMBLED.  IT WAS THEN CHECKED FOR ANY FURTHER LEAKS AND NONE WERE DISCOVERED.  THE CAR WAS THEN SECURED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.
NO REMARKS

column168: THE DRIVER GATHERING CRUDE OIL FROM TWO PRODUCTION TANKS IN A HILLY, REMOTE AREA. HE WANTED TO LOAD THE TRAILER COMPARTMENT OF THE CARGO TANK CLOSEST TO THE TRACTOR'S DRIVE AXLE TO PROVIDE GOOD TRACTION SINCE HE HAD TO BACK DOWN A HILL ON THE LEASE ROAD AFTER LOADING. THE COMPARTMENT LOADED QUICKER THAN NORMAL CAUSING THE COMPARTMENT TO OVERFILL BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD CHANGE THE FLOW TO ANOTHER COMPARTMENT. THE DRIVER CONTACTED OUR OFFICE VIA COMPANY RADIO AND OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND PEAT-SORB.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER OHIO E.P.A. AND THE SUPERVISOR FOR THE PERRY STATE FOREST WERE NOTIFIED.

THE HOSE ON THE LOADING LINE CAME UNCONNECTED WHILE LOADING A CARGO TANK WITH SULFURIC ACID. THE OPERATOR FAILED TO NOTICE IT IMMEDIATELY AND SULFURIC ACID WAS PUMPED ONTO THE GROUND FOR SEVERAL MINUTES BEFORE THE OPERATOR REALIZED WHAT HAD HAPPENED. WHEN THE OPERATOR NOTICED IT HE SHUT OFF THE LOADING PUMP, CLOSED THE LOADING VALVE AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISION. THE COMPANY SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED IN TO NEUTRALIZE AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. APPROXIMATELY 80 YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED AT PINE TREE WASTE, INC., A SPECIAL WASTE LANDFILL. THE OPERATOR WAS DISCHARGED FOR INATTENTIVENESS AND IMPROPERLY CONNECTING THE LOADING HOSE.

column168: ROLLOVER ACCIDENT

GREEN BROTHERS OIL  CO RECEIVED A CALL FROM YOUR REPRESENTATIVE,  MR TOM HARE STATING THAT THE FUEL TANK AT THE JANUS BUILDING WAS EMPTY AND REQUESTED WE DISPATCH A DRIVER ASAP WITH FUEL FOR THE GENERATOR.  OUR DRIVER, MR RONY GRAMAJO ARRIVED WITHIN AN HOUR AND COMMENCED PUMPING FUEL. THE GAUGE ON THE TANK READ EMPTY AND AFTER DISCHARGING THE FUEL NOZZLE, THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE TRUCK TO GET A SECOND HOSE.  AS HE WAS AT THE TRUCK, THE TANK BEGAN TO OVERFILL.  WHEN THE DRIVER RETURNED TO OUR YARD, WE TOPPED OFF HIS FUEL TANK WITH APPROX 10 GALLONS.  TO BEGIN, OUR FUELING PROCEDURES STATE THAT THE DRIVER SHOULD NEVER WALK AWAY FROM A NOZZLE THAT IS DISCHARGING FUEL.  OUR DRIVER DID NOT COMPLY WITH THOSE PROCEDURES AND WAS THE CAUSE OF THE FUEL SPILL.  HOWEVER, WE ARE EQUIPPED TO HANDLE SPILLS OF THIS NATURE AND ALL OF OUR TRUCKS ARE EQUIPPED WITH SPILL CONTAINMENT MATERIAL.  IF THE SPILL HAD REMAINED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA OF THE FUEL TANK ROOM, IT WOULD HAVE BEEN IMMEDIATELY RECTIFIED.  THE FUEL SPILL PROBLEM WAS EXACERBATED BY THE FACT THAT A HOLE HAD BEEN DRILLED IN THE CONTAINMENT ROOM THROUGH TO THE PARKING GARAGE AND EVIDENTLY INTO SOME STORAGE SPACES AS WELL AS THE SUMP/DRAIN AREA  I DO NOT KNOW IF THIS WAS DONE BY CSI AS PART OF THE INSTALLATION OR BY CRESCENT REAL ESTATE AFTER THE INSTALLATION WAS COMPLETE.  IN EITHER CASE, THIS BREACH OF CONTAINMENT WAS THE MAIN REASON FOR THE EXTENSIVE CLEANUP PROCEDURES.  AS I STATED EARLIER, OUR DRIVER WAS AT FAULT FOR THE INITIAL SPILL, BUT GIVEN THE CIRCUMSTANCES GREEN BROTHERS OIL CO SHOULD NOT BE SOLELY RESPONSIBLE FOR THE COST OF THE CLEANUP.

column168: PRODUCT WAS BEING PUMPED FROM THE DELIVERY TRUCK INTO A 3000 GALLON TANK. DURING TANK FILLING, PRODUCT FLOWED OUT OF THE TANK THROUGH THE DRAWDOWN TUBE. THE VALVE ON THE DRAWDOWN TUBE HAD BEEN ACCIDENTLY LEFT OPEN BY CONSTRUCTION PERSONNEL FOLLOWING A HYDROSTATIC TEST OF THE NEW TANK 2 WEEKS EARLIER. A DRAIN VALVE IN THE TANKS SECONDARY CONTAINMENT CONCRETE STRUCTURE HAD ALSO BEEN LEFT OPEN, ALLOWING RELEASED MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE TANK SYSTEM. THE DRAWDOWN TUBE WAS CLOSED AS SOON AS SAFE ACCESS WAS POSSIBLE. RELEASED MATERIAL FLOWED INTO AN OPEN STORM DRAIN, BUT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY COLLECTED AND CONTAINED IN THE SITE'S STORM WATER RETENTION POND. THE WATER/PRODUCT CONTENTS OF THE POND WERE PUMPED INTO A NEIGHBORING COUNTY DRAINAGE CANAL UPON APPROVAL OF THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION. NO TREATMENT WAS REQUIRED. AFFECTED TANK AND STORM SEWER AREAS WERE FLUSHED WITH WATER. NO INJURY OCCURRED.

column168: ON 04/13/01 AT APPROX. 0900HRS, OUR LOADER HAD JUST FINISHED TRANSLOADING A LOAD OF SULPHURIC ACID FROM A RAILCAR INTO A TANKER TRUCK, OWNED BY EASTERNCARTAGE OF COPPERHILL TENNESSEE, WHEN THE DRIVER FAILED TO CHECK HIS HOSE CONNECTION AS PER SOP AND DROVE OFF WITH THE HOSE STILL CONNECTED. THIS CAUSED THE VALVE AT THE TOP OF THE RAILCAR TO BREAK, CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO SPILL TO THE GROUND. CONTAINMENT WAS IN PLACE AND NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO THE SEWER SYSTEM. FERGUSON HARBOR WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND CLEANED UP THE SURFACE AREA AND TREATED AND NEUTRALIZED THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE SPILL BASIN/CONTAINMENT POND. THREE EMPLOYEES WHO WERE IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO THE SPILL WERE TAKEN TO ERLANGER HOSPITAL AS PRECAUTION, TREATED AND RELEASED. CORRECTIVE ACTION AT THE TIME WAS TO TAKE THE KEYS FROM THE DRIVER AND SECURE THE VEHICLE UNTIL READY FOR DEPARTURE. HOWEVER WE NO LONGER TRANSFER HAZMAT AT THIS FACILITY.

column168: WHEN THE DRIVER OPEN HIS TRAILER AT HIS FIRST STOP HE ENCOUNTERED A POWERFUL ODOR OF A SOLVENT.  HE HAS DRUMS OF VARIOUS PRODUCTS ON BOARD, ANY OF WHICH COULD BE AT FAULT.  AFTER UNLOADING AT THAT STOP HE DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM HAS LEAKED A CONSIDERABLE QUANTITY OF LIQUID ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. SOME OF IT HAS ESCAPED ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD THAT THE TRUCK IS PARKED ON. CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. DUE TO THE ODOR IN THE BUILDING, THE FACILITY MANAGER ALSO SUSPENDED WORK IN THE AREA AND EVACUATED HIS EMPLOYEES TO ANOTHER AREA.  GIVEN ALL OF THE DATA AVAILABLE AT THE TIME, IT WAS BELIEVED THAT A SHIPMENT OF RESIN SOLUTION WAS LEAKING.  CARRIER'S HAZMAT SPECIALIST CONTACTED A SPILL CONTRACTOR FOR  A RESPONSE.  AFTER BEING NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER OF THE RESIN SOLUTION FAXED AN M.S.D.S. FOR THEIR PRODUCT.  THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED, AND BASED ON AVAILABLE INFORMATION, DETERMINED THAT ENTRY ON SUPPLIED AIR WOULD BE NEEDED. AFTER UNLOADING MUCH OF THE LOAD, A DRUM OF INK WAS FOUND WITH A HOLE IN ITS BOTTOM THERE WAS NO CORRESPONDING CAUSE.  INK HAD RUN THE ENTIRE LENGTH OF THE TRAILER, WITH  SOME HAVING SPLASHED ONTO OTHER SHIPMENTS.  THE CONTRACTOR SPREAD OIL DRY ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR TO ABSORB THE FREE LIQUIDS.  THEY OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM AND TIGHTENED THE VENT BUNG ON ONE OTHER DRUM.  AFTER CONSULTATION WITH THE CARRIER IT WAS DECIDED TO TAKE THE TRAILER TO THE CONTRACTOR'S FACILITY AND PARK IT THERE FOR THE NIGHT WITH DOORS OPEN. THE CONTRACTOR SPREAD PLASTIC FILM UNDER THE TRAILER AND WATCHED FOR ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  THE DRIVER CALLED THE NEXT DAY TO REPORT THAT HE HAD DROPPED THE TRAILER AT THE CONTRACTOR'S FACILITY AS PLANNED AND HAD GONE TO A NEARBY TRUCK STOP FOR THE NIGHT.  HE RETURNED TO FIND THAT A SMALL QUANTITY OF DRIPPED OUT OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE SHEETING, BUT IT APPEARS TO HAVE STOPPED. AFTER DISCUSSION WITH THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT SPECIALIST IT WAS DECIDED THAT IT WOULD BE SAFE TO CONTINUE THE TRAILER TO A NEARBY FACILITY OF THE CARRIER IT WAS UNLOADED THERE AND SURVEYED.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TO BE SENT TO THE CARRIER'S HOME FACILITY FOR INSPECTION AND DOCUMENTATION THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

PAILS WERE AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ON A SHEET OF CARDBOARD, ON A PALLET, EMITTING AN ODOR OF VINEGAR. A DOCK EMPLOYEE OBSERVED THAT. THAT SHEET OF CARDBOARD WAS SATURATED WITH LIQUID. INSPECTION OF THE SHIPMENT DISCLOSED LOOSE FILL CAPS ON TWO PAILS. THE CAPS WERE TIGHTENED, THE PAILS WERE RINSED OFF AND SHIPPED ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

THE UNLOADING AREA IS LOCATED ON UNLEVEL GROUND WHICH CAUSED PRODUCT TO ACCUMULATE TO THE RIGHT SIDE.  A CONTROL VALVE STUCK OPEN ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ENTER THE COLLECTION HOOD WHICH WAS TORN. IT WAS RAINING AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS WASHED INTO A STORM DRAIN SYSTEM AND ENDED UP IN THE REACTOR-COOLING POND.  LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP WAS CONTACTED FOR REMEDIATION.  THE TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED OUT OF SERVICE AND REPAIRS WERE DONE THE NEXT DAY (SEE ATTACHED).
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A TANKER TRUCK PULLING A SET OF DOUBLE TANKERS ENTERED THE WEST GATE OF HILL AFB AT APPROXIMATELY 5:45 AM.  THE ROAD AT THIS POINT RISES UP A HILL. THE DRIVER REALIZED HE WAS IN TOO HIGH OF A GEAR AND POWERED OUT TO GET INTO A LOWER GEAR.  THE TRUCK AND DOUBLE TANKERS ROLLED BACK INTO A CONCRETE ABUTMENT PUNCTURING A HOLE IN THE REAR TANKER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED UP TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND SUMMONED HELP FROM HILL AFB PEOPLE.  THEY WERE ABLE TO CONTAIN BETWEEN 1200 TO 1400 GALLONS IN THIS AREA AND PUMP OFF THE LEAKING TANKER.  APPROXIMATELY 500 TO 700 GALLONS ENTERED THE STORM DRAIN.  MONTGOMERY WATSON AND TW COMPANY WERE CALLED FOR THE CLEAN UP OF THE SPILL.
WHILE FILLING A HOME HEATING TANK A FUNNEL FELL FROM THE FILL PIPE & OIL SPILLED ONTO THE BLACK TOP.

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, DON JENKS WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF LEAKING TANK CAR IN BEAUMONT YARD. JENKS CONTACTED TOSCO REFINING AT SMITH'S BLUFF TX, THE CONSIGNEE, BUT THEY WOULD NOT PROVIDE ASSISTANCE. IT WAS ALSO DETERMINED THAT THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS DEFECTIVE, BECAUSE IT WOULD NOT REGISTER THE CORRECT LIQUID LEVEL.  2500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS OFFLOADED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR INTERCHANGE TO KCS AND DELIVERY TO TOSCO REFINING.

column168: MANWAY COVER WAS LOOSE. GARNER INC. CALLED OUT TO TIGHTEN COVER. ONE EMPLOYEE STATED HE FELT ILL. SWITCHMAN RANDY HILL WAS TAKEN TO EMERGENCY ROOM. AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 PM ON APRIL 6, 2001 I RECEIVED A CALL THAT SWITCHMAN RANDY HILL HAD REPORTED A SMELL FROM TANK CAR GATX 90224 WHICH WAS LOCATED ON NOPB TRACK 21. OUR HAZ-MAT RESPONSE PLAN WAS ACTIVATED. UPON ARRIVAL, THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ALREADY BEEN ON THE SCENE. AN ODOR WAS DETECTED IN THE AREA AROUND THE TANK CAR IN QUESTION. I CONTACTED GARNER INC. TO COME OUT AND INVESTIGATE. GARNER FOUND THAT THE MANWAY COVER ON THIS CAR WAS LOOSE,/. IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THERE WERE DIFFERENT SIZE NUTS IN USE ON THE HOLD DOWN STUDS. AFTER GARNER TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER THE ODOR BEGAN TO DISSIPATE. CAR WAS RELEASE TO PROCEED. SWITCHMAN RANDY HILL REPORTED FEELING BAD AND REQUESTED TO BE TAKEN FOR MEDICAL EXAMINATION. MANAGER JOHN MORROW TOOK MR. HILL TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM FOR TREATMENT. AFTER CHECKING IN AT THE EMERGENCY ROOM AND SITTING FOR A PERIOD OF TIME MR. FILE 3063 D, SHIPPER: CONSUMERS FLAVORING, AWB# BKL 3843415781 CHA. ON 04/02/01 AT 0236, A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR HAZMAT SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177. PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIANS WILLIAM HENDERSON AND PAUL SCHMIDT, AND HAZMAT COORDINATOR CHARLES JONES, DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE AND EMITTING AN ODOR. THEY OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX IN QUESTION AND BEGAN INSPECTING THE INNER CONTENTS WHICH WAS PACKED IN STYROFOAM PEANUTS. DURING THEIR INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THEY FOUND 24 X 4 OUNCES EACH GLASS RECEPTACLES. WHILE CHECKING EACH INDIVIDUAL GLASS RECEPTACLES THEY DISCOVERED TWO OF THE 24 GLASS RECEPTACLES BROKEN. ONE GLASS RECEPTACLE CONTAINING 4 FLUID OUNCES OF ARTIFICIAL BLV FLAVOR NO. 2128, FLASH POINT 116 DEGREES F. WAS MISSING THE ENTIRE BOTTOM, CAUSE UNKNOWN. THE OTHER GLASS RECEPTACLE CONTAINING 4 OUNCES OF ARTIFICIAL SWEET DOUGH FLAVOR EMULSION NO. 11423. FLASH POINT 109 DEGREES F. WAS MISSING THE CLOSURE WHICH HAD CRACKED DURING TRANSIT AND WAS FOUND AMONG ALL THE OTHER GLASS RECEPTACLES. ALL OF THE INNER GLASS RECEPTACLES WERE INDIVIDUALLY WRAPPED IN PLASTIC BUBBLE WRAP AND IDENTIFIED WITH A RED MAGIC MARKER OF THEIR CONTENTS ON MASKING TAPE. THIS PACKAGE DID NOT CONTAIN ANY ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL IN THE EVENT OF LEAKAGE. THE SPILL TEAM PLACED THE SHIPMENT IN 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD, AND THEN PLACED THE ENTIRE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO THE INTENDED CONSIGNEE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND HAD PROPER SHIPPER'S DECLARATION ACCOMPANYING IT. THE AREA INVOLVED IS A WELL VENTILATED AREA AND ONLY ONE EMPLOYEE WAS INVOLVED. THIS EMPLOYEE, A FEMALE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS AND SHE RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA AFTER THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA. THIS EMPLOYEE REQUIRED NO MEDICAL ATTENTION, THEREFORE NO FOLLOW-UP WAS NECESSARY. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT AND PICTURES TAKEN ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE. SPILL TEAM CLEAR OF SCENE AT 0251.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. THERE WAS SLIGHT STAIN AND ODOR NOTICED WITH THE OUTER PACKAGING.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM WITHOUT OPENING THE BOX.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TO BE DELIVERED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE PER REQUEST OF THE SHIPPER.

UPON ARRIVAL SHE DONNED HER PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND OPENED THE EXPRESS PACK IN QUESTION AND FOUND A 1 X 11 OUNCE AEROSOL METAL RECEPTACLE THAT HAD LEAKED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS, SHE OBSERVED THAT THE PLASTIC CAP THAT PROTECTED THE DIAPERSANT BUTTON WAS JUST LAYING INSIDE OF THE EXPRESS ENVELOPE NOTHING THAT IT HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THE PLASTIC EXPRESS ENVELOPE DID NOT HAVE ANY MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION ATTACHED OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL. column168: FILE:3066D, SHIPPER: CROSSLAND, AWB# RDU 5518409231 GS0. ON 04/12/2001 AT 2342 A SPILL WAS CALLED IN AT PRIMARY "B" DIVERTER 1, "B" BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE,  Wilmington, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS RANDY WILLIAMS AND TIM HINES RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY OBSERVED A PACKAGE SHOWING SIGNS OF LEAKAGE AND ALSO NOTICED A CHERRY TYPE ODOR WHICH ACCORDING TO THE MARKINGS ON THE BOX WAS CONSISTANT.  THE TEAM THEN BACKED OUT TO DON THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, ONCE DONNING THIS EQUIPMENT THE TEAM RE-ENTERED THE AREA AND ONCE AGAIN APPROACH THE ABOVE PACKAGE.  THE TEAM TESTED THE LEAKING PRODUCT AND THE PH PAPER SHOWED THAT THE PH LEVEL WAS 11 WHICH INDICATED THAT THE CONTENTS WAS  A CAUSTIC MATERIAL.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING PACKAGE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PACKAGE HAD A PRE-PRINTED HAZARD CLASS CORROSIVE LABEL AND THE PROPEWR SHIPPING NAME "PHOSPHORIC ACID SOLUTION, UN1808".  THE SHIPMENT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED AND REMOVED FROM THE AREA, THE HAZ MAT SPILL TEAM NEUTRALIZED THE AFFECTED AREAS AND RETURNED THE SHIPMENT TO THE HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT THE SAME ABOVE ADDRESS.  THE INNER PLASTIC 2.5 GALLON BOTTLE LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES DUE TO THE CLOSURE NOT BEING SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS AS STATED EARLIER PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, BUT A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS DID NOT ACCOMPANY IT DURING TRANSPORTATION THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A DOT SPECIFICATION RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD FOR THE PROPER SHIPPING  DOCUMENTATION. THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE THAT CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE LEAKING PRODUCT, BUT HE HAD SURGICAL GLOVES ON AND NO KIN CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THIS INDIVIDUAL, THEREFORE NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS REQUIRED AND NO FURTHER FOLLOW-UP WAS DEEMED NECESSARY. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN MICHEAL COOK RESPONDED DONNING HIS PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT. COOK THEN OPENED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND 1 METAL INNER CAN THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING AROUND THE TOP NEAR THE CLOSURE. ONLY ONE EMPLOYEE WAS IN CONTACT VIA ODOR ONLY IN THE AREA WHICH IS A WELL VENTILATED BUILDING.  SHE WAS ADVISED OF THE WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND SHE RETURNED TO WORK. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION OR FOLLOW-UP WAS REQUIRED. CLEAR OF SCENE: 03:03 NOTE: DIGITAL PHOTO'S WERE TAKEN AND ARE ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS ON CURTIS AVENUE TRAVELING AT APPROX 25MPH THE DRIVER APPLIED THE BRAKES TO SLOW DOWN AROUND AN UP-COMING SHARP CARVE.   AT THAT TIME THE DRIVER STATED THAT THE TRUCK STARTED TO SLIDE ALMOST AS IF ITS WERE DRIVING ON ICE.  THE TRUCK SLID SIDEWAYS AND HIT A SERIES OF BAD RUTS IN THE ROAD. (THIS ROAD IS USED TO ENTER CURTIS BAY, AN OIL LOADING TERMINAL SERVING THIS AREA) THE "ICE" FEELING THAT THE DRIVER NOTICED WAS CAUSED BY SOME # 2 HEATING OIL ON THE ROAD SURFACE THAT BECAME EVEN SLICKER WHEN IT BEGAN TO RAIN. THE TRUCK OVERTURNED COMING TO REST ON ITS TOP. ON 04/16/2001 OUR DRIVER, MR. JAMES DRIVER WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 25MPH ALONG CURTIS AVENUE AT PENNINGTON AVENUE IN BALTIMORE, MARYLAND.  MR. DRIVER STATED THAT HE APPLIED THE BRAKES ATTEMPTING TO SLOW THE VEHICLE PRIOR TO ENTERING A SHARP CURVE IN THE ROAD.  WHEN HE BEGAN BRAKING, THE TRUCK STARTED TO SLIDE SIDEWAYS ON THE ROAD MADE RECENTLY SLIPPERY BY A MISTING RAIN THAT WAS FALLING THAT MORNING.  IT WAS LATER LEARNED THAT ROAD WAS ALSO SLICK WITH HEATING OIL THAT SPILLED OFF OF THE TOPS OF HEATING OIL TRUCKS THAT LOAD AT THE TERMINAL ACCESSED BY THIS ROAD. THE TRUCK NOW SLIDING SIDEWAYS, HIT A SERIES OF RUTS IN THE ROAD SURFACE (ALSO CAUSED BY THE UNUSUALLY HEAVY TRUCK TRAFFIC).  UPON HITTING THE RUTS THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE FINALLY COMING TO REST ON THE TOP OF THE CAB AND TANKS.  THE DRIVER TURNED OFF THE IGNITION AND CLIMBED OUT OF THE TRUCK, IMMEDIATELY NOTIFYING OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL OF THE INCIDENT.  THE DRIVER REPORTED TO OUR EMERGENCY STAFF THAT WHEN THE TRUCK HAD ROLLED ON TOP OF THE TANKS, A VALVE ON TOP OF THE TANK WAS BROKEN OFF, CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO SPILL AT A VERY SLOW RATE ON TO THE GROUND. OUR EMERGENCY STAFF OF 5 PEOPLE WENT TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP AND RIGHTING OF OUR DAMAGED TRUCK.  UPON REACHING THE SCENE IT WAS DETERMINED BY OUR STAFF THAT THE CLEAN UP TIME WOULD BE GREATLY REDUCED IF WE HIRED AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR TO VACUUM UP THE SPILLED SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE.  THE NEAREST CONTRACTOR ON OUR APPROVED CONTRACTORS LIST WAS DISPATCHED.  A TRUCK TOWING COMPANY WAS DISPATCHED BY OUR STAFF WHILE EN-ROUTE.  THE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR ARRIVED WITH A VACUUM TRUCK AND QUICKLY BEGAN TO SUCK UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  AFTER THE CONTRACTOR FINISHED, THE TRUCK WAS RIGHTED BY OUR TOW COMPANY AND OUR EMERGENCY STAFF MADE A FINAL SWEEP THROUGH THE SCENE TO GATHER UP INFORMATION FOR LATER USE AT OUR HAZMAT TRAINING SESSIONS. THE CONTRACTOR  HAULED THE CLEANED UP PRODUCT BACK TO HOLDING TANKS AT AMATO TO BE TESTED AND PUMPED BACK INTO OUR STORAGE TANKS. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS COMPLETELY RECOVERED, THEREFORE NO HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST WAS NECESSARY, AND NO DISPOSAL WAS NECESSARY. THE BOTTOM LINE OF THIS INCIDENT IS: ** NO DRIVER INJURY. ** NO OTHER VEHICLES OR PERSONS INVOLVED. ** REMOTE, INDUSTRIAL LOCATION, LITTLE TO NO PROPERTY DAMAGE. ** PRODUCT RECOVERED.

column168: THE DRUM WAS ON A TRAILER THAT HAD JUST CAME IN FROM MAKING AREA PICKUPS. MIKE BARRY WAS OPERATING THE FORKLIFT.  TRANSFERRING THE MATERIAL ON TO A TRAILER BOUND FOR THE FACILITY/DESTINATION ADDRESS (POLLUTION CONTROL INDUSTRIES).  MIKE HAD ALREADY LOADED SEVERAL OF THE DRUMS WHEN HE TRIED TO PICK UP THE DRUM THAT ENDED UP GETTING PUNCTURED, HE MADE CONTACT WITH THE DRUM TOO FAST, AND WITH THE DRUM GRABBER SET TOO HIGH.  THIS CAUSED THE DRUM TO PUNCTURE, AND WHEN HE LOWERED THE DRUM GRABBER THE PUNCTURE BECAME A TEAR.  THE DRUM WAS THEN IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED AND ALL OF THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS CONTAINED AND ABSORBED WITH NON COMBUSTIBLE ABSORBENT.  MIKE BARRY WAS GIVEN A VERBAL WARNING, AND THE PROCEDURES FOR USING A FORKLIFT WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE REVIEWED.

ON LOADING AIRCRAFT AA N537 A STRONG ODOR WAS DETECTED IN THE CARGO BIN BY AA FLEET SERVICE CLERK EMPLOYEES WHO DESCRIBED SYMPTOMS OF LIGHT HEADEDNESS FROM VAPOR. THE BOX DESCRIBED WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN SEVEN - 1 LITRE CONTAINERS OF PAINT RELATED MATERIAL UN1263, CLASS 3 FLAMMABLE LIQUID, ONE OF WHICH WAS DENTED AND RELEASED CONTENTS FROM THE SCREW - ON TOP.  BOX WAS MARKED WITH A FLAMMABLE SYMBOL AND ORIENTATION ARROWS IMPROPERLY PACKED AND TENDERED AS A MAIL ITEM BY NIPPON BEE CHEMICAL CO LTD, OSAKA JAPAN.  THE FLIGHT INCIDENT DESCRIBED ON ASSOCIATED FORM F5800.  1 RESULTED IN AMERICAN AIRLINES AIRCRAFT N537 REMOVAL FROM SERVICE FOR DURATION OF 154 MINUTES DURING IDENTIFICATION AND CLEANING OF THE UNKNOWN SPILL FROM EMS INTERNATIONAL MAIL.  THE TOTAL DELAY OF FLIGHT AA0481 DFW-MEX WHILE OBTAINING REPLACEMENT AIRCRAFT WAS 98 MINUTES WITH A SUBSEQUENT ASSOCIATED DELAY OF 54 MINUTES TO FLIGHT AA420 DFW-YYZ. TELEPHONE CONTACTS LISTED FOR THE MAIL SHIPPER, NIPPON BEE CHEMICAL CO, OSAKA JAPAN ARE:  072-857-5530  072-857-8500-FAX INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO USPS INSPECTOR CARL KANOSKI (TELEPHONE 817-684-7999). DURING FLIGHT CONTENTS ON THESE BOTTLES LEAKED FROM OVERHEAD. THIS BLEACH AFFECTED OTHER PASSENGERS AS WELL AS 10 AIRCRAFT SEATS. TWA FIRST OFFICER AND FLIGHT ATTENDANT ATTEMPTED CLEAN-  UP DURING FLIGHT AND WAS OVER-COME WITH FUMES AND REQUIRED OXYGEN.
