column168: NARRATIVE: ACE DRIVER MATT WRIGHT WAS DELIVERING ROUTE 852 ON TRAILER NA889 AT AN ACE STORE IN MONROE MI (PH 734-243-6180). A 4 GALLON CASE OF LIQUID FIRE HAD BEEN DROPPED HARD ON THE  TRAILER FLOOR BY A STORE EMPLOYEE FROM THE PREVIOUS STOP. ONE OF THE GALLON CONTAINERS HAD LEAKED SO WHEN MATT OPENED THE REAR TRAILER DOOR AT THE MONROE STORE HE WAS SPLASHED WITH LIQUID FIRE ON HIS ARMS AND BACK OF NECK. STORE EMPLOYEES HELPED MATT REMOVE HIS JACKET AND SHIRT AND THEN ASSISTED MATT WASHING OFF HIS NECK, BACK, ARMS, AND CHEST. MATT HAD A SPARE SHIRT WHICH HE PUT ON. SODA ASH WAS USED BY MATT TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID SPILL IN THE  TRAILER BUT SPILLED PRODUCT IN THE CUSTOMERS DRIVE WAS COVERED  WITH OIL DRI. CORPORATE LP REPRESENTATIVES WERE NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT AND INFOTRAC WAS CONTACTED. THE STORE OWNER AL WAS THEN GIVEN INSTRUCTIONS OVER THE PHONE HOW TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL IN HIS DRIVEWAY. AL DID NOT WISH TO ADDRESS CLEAN UP BUT WANTED ACE TO TAKE CARE OF IT. AT 1 PM MATT RETURNED FROM HIS ROUTE AND INFORMED MYSELF AND BILL HEBAN WHAT HAPPENED. MATT COMPLETED A SHORT FORM ACCIDENT REPORT TO DOCUMENT HIS INJURY. MATT SIGNED THE WAIVER FOR EMERGENCY TREATMENT. MATT'S JACKET AND SHIRT HAD HOLES EATEN THROUGH BUT WAS ONLY EXPOSED IN BACK OF HIS NECK THERE MATT HAS A RED  MARK THE SIZE OF A QUARTER. I HAD MATT WASH HIS NECK OFF AGAIN BEFORE SENDING HIM HOME. AT 2:30 THIS OFFICER WENT TO THE MONROE ACE WITH A CORROSIVES HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPILL CLEAN UP KIT AND SAFELY CLEANED UP THE SPILL. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE TOLEDO RSC IN THE OFFICERS OWN VEHICLE. THE CONTAINERS STILL INTACT WILL BE USED AS PRODUCT BY LOCAL CONTRACTORS. SPILLED PRODUCT WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH EPA REGULATIONS.

A CONNECTING PASSENGER FROM KOREAN AIRLINES TO AMERICAN AIRLINES HAD A CHECKED BAG THAT EMITTING STRONG FUMES.  DURING THE LOADING PROCESS, AN AMERICAN AIRLINES EMPLOYEE WAS OVERWHELMED BY THE BAG CONTENTS AND SUFFERED FROM NAUSEA AND VOMITING.  THE AMERICAN AIRLINES EMPLOYEE WAS SENT TO MEDICAL FOR OBSERVATION.  THE CHECKED BAG WAS CONFISCATED IN LAX FOR AN FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE PRODUCT WAS DETERMINED TO  BE AN INDUSTRIAL GLUE/ADHESIVE USED IN THE MANUFACTURING OF CLOTHES.  THE PASSENGER STARTED HIS TRIP IN KOREA WITH A FINAL DESTINATION OF SANTO DOMINGO, DOMINICAN REPUBLIC.  ACCORDING TO THE PRODUCT INFORMATION, PROVIDED BY THE MANUFACTURE IN KOREA, 36% OF THE ACTIVE INGREDIENT IS BUTYL ACRYLATE AND THEREFORE WAS PROVIDED AS THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME WITH UN2348 AS THE IDENTIFICATION NUMBER.

PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIAN TIMOTHY HINES DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A LAB PACK THAT HAD VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE SEAPING FROM THE PACKAGE. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN A PLASTIC ZIP LOCK BAGGIE, WITH A PLASTIC "PAIL" INSIDE. THE PLASTIC "PAIL" HAD A PLASTIC SNAP ON LID, WHICH DID NOT HAVE POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE, CAUSING IT TO LEAK IT'S ENTIRE CONTENTS. THIS CONTAINED A MASS BEING SENT FOR BIOPSY, SURROUNDED BY APPROXIMATELY 2 QUARTS OF FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION. THIS SHIPMENT CAUSED OUR EXPRESS SORT AREA (HIGH PRIORITY) TO BE SHUT DOWN FOR 86 MINUTES. WE HAD TO REMOVE THE LATERAL  BELT AND ROLLERS TO BE DECONNED DUE TO THE ODOR PERMATING THIS EQUIPMENT. THE AREA INVOLVED WAS WELL VENTILATED AND WASHED WITH SOAP AND WATER BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED THERE WERE 8 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA WITH THE EXCEPTION OF ONE. SHE WAS TREATED BY OUR EMS DEPARTMENT AND THEN SENT TO THE HOSPITAL AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE ONLY. (SHE HAS PRIOR MEDICAL HISTORY NOT RELATED TO THIS SPILL). THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABEL, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED MATERIAL. A COPY OF THE MSDS HAD BEEN OBTAINED, GIVEN TO THE EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT, AND WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. THERE ARE PICTURE ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE AT ILN CLEAR OF SCENE 0322.

ON APRIL 23, 2001, PASSENGER TRAVELING FROM LAX TO MIA BOARDED AA FLIGHT 651 WITH UNDECLARED BOTTLE OF LIQUID PESTICIDE AS CARRY-ON BAGGAGE.  DURING FLIGHT, THE BOTTLE CAP BROKE OFF CAUSING THE LIQUID PESTICIDE TO LEAK ONTO THE AIRCRAFT CARPETING, AND DISSEMINATE TOXIC VAPORS INTO THE CABIN.  AN AIR DIVERSION WAS INITIATED AND THE AIRCRAFT LANDED WITH OUT INCIDENT IN PHOENIX.  THREE PEOPLE WERE TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION AND RELEASED.  THIRTEEN OTHER PEOPLE WERE PLACED UNDER OBSERVATION FOR AN HOUR AT THE AIRPORT.  ALL INJURIES WERE NON-LIFE THREATENING.  AFTER THE PLANE WAS EVACUATED, AN AUTHORIZED SPILL CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT 1215 HOURS.  SIX HOURS LATER THE AIRCRAFT WAS CLEARED FOR MAINTENANCE TO REPLACE THE SOILED CARPET AND SEAT COVERS, AND FOR THE GROUND CREW TO CLEAN OFF LUGGAGE AND REDISTRIBUTE TO PASSENGERS.  THE PASSENGERS CARRYING ON THE PESTICIDE WERE REROUTED TO MIA ONBOARD AN OTHER CARRIER.  ALL ADDITIONAL PASSENGERS WERE ACCOMMODATED ON AA FLIGHT TO MIA.  ALL CONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE CONTAINED AND PROPERLY MANIFESTED AND DISPOSED.

AT  8:45 AM ON APRIL 24, 2001, RICK KRAFT WAS ADVISED THAT A SMALL POISON GAS RELEASE HAD OCCURRED ON THE DOCK AT THE RICHFIELD SERVICE CENTER.  THE DOCKMAN WHO UNLOADED THE TRAILER HAD ONE OR TWO CYLINDERS THAT HAD LEAKED SOME BROWNISH VAPORS.  THE DOCKMAN TRANSFERRED THE CYLINDERS TO AN EMPTY STORAGE TRAILER AWAY FROM THE REST OF THE DOCK OPERATION.  THE SERVICE CENTER MANAGER-BOB KANE- WENT TO THE DOCK AND OBSERVED THE CYLINDERS AND HAD THE TRAILER MOVED TO THE YARD AND THE DOORS CLOSED.  BOB KANE THEN CALLED THE LOCAL MAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AT 8:55 AM AND THEY WERE ON THE SCENE AT 9:03 AM.  HE THEN CONTACTED THE CORPORATE SAFETY MANAGER FOR WARD TRUCKING, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE OHIO EPA BETWEEN 9:00 AND 9:05.  BOB SPOKE TO A MR. JONES AT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND WAS GIVEN INCIDENT #563832.  HE ALSO SPOKE WITH A MR.  HOLMES AT THE OHIO EPA AND WAS GIVEN REPORT NUMBER 0104-77-1398. THE LOCAL HAZ MAT TEAM REPORTED THAT THEY GOT A "O" READING FROM THEIR METERS FOR ANY GASSES  IN THE TRAILER AND/OR AROUND THE CYLINDERS AND ADVISED THAT ALL THAT NEEDED TO BE DONE WAS TO WAIT FOR THE CONSIGNEE TO ARRIVE AND INSPECT THE CYLINDERS AND REMOVE THEM. THIS TOOK PLACE ON THURSDAY, APRIL 26, 2001.  THE CONSIGNEE HAS CONTRACTED WITH THE MATHESON GAS COMPANY IN TWINSBURG OHIO TO DO THE INSPECTION AND TRANSPORT THE CYLINDERS TO THE CONSIGNEE IN TOLEDO OHIO. THE DOCKMAN WENT TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM AT AKRON GENERAL HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT AND WAS GIVEN A CLEAN BILL OF HEALTH.  HE STATED THAT HE FELT NO ILL EFFECTS.

A LARGE SCALE CLEAN UP TOOL PLACE INVOLVING GUARDIAN ENV CLEANUP AND PA DEP.  THE ACCIDENT HAD HIGH NITRATE LEVELS WHICH WAS A CONCERN TO THE PHILADELPHIA SUBURBAN H20 COMPANY.  THE STREAM WAS DIKED AND CHARCOAL ADDED.  A VACUUM TRUCK WAS ALSO ON SITE.

column168: DSR DAVE ERNE WAS UNLOADING AN APPOINTMENT SECURITY TRAILER 715-3194.  HE CAME TO ME, BYRON BOHANON, FOS(XIN) AND INFORMED ME THAT WHEN HE SET ONE OF THE SKIDS ON DOCK, HE NOTICED SOME LIGHT POWDER COME OFF SKID.  UPON INVESTIGATION, WE NOTICED THAT A VERY MINUTE AMOUNT HAD COME OUT OF ONE BAG ON BOTTOM OF SKID(STILL DO NOT KNOW IN BAG IS PUNCTURED).  ALSO, ONE BAG PROBABLY CAUGHT A TRAILER WALL AND PUT VERY SMALL HOLE IN BAG (THIS IS STILL COVERED BY ORIGINAL SHRINK WRAP.  I CALLED CHEM TREC AND THEY IN TURN CALLED INFO TRAC.  DAN AT INFO TRAC IS HAVING US HOLD AND ISOLATE SHIPMENT ON TRAILER UNTIL THEY CAN CONTACT SYNGENTA CROP PROTECTION.

DSR ELLIOT RUIZ UNLOADED SKID CONTAINING 27 CTNS OF (ETHANOL, ETHANOL ISOPROPANOL).  ONE OF THESE CTNS WERE CRUSHED, WEDGED IN BETWEEN A SKID. DSR PULLED SKID OUT OF TRAILER AND BOX FELL OFF THE SIDE OF SKID.  THE TOP OF THE BOX WAS RIPPED OPEN ABOUT 5 - 8OZ. OF FLUID POURED OUT.  FLUID FROM THE CARTON EVAPORATED.  CALLED CHEMTREC AND THEY INFORMED ME THAT NO CHEMICAL CLEANUP WAS REQUIRED ALSO INFORMED ME TO SECURE CTN IN A SALVAGE DRUM UNTIL SHIPPER & CONSIGNEE IS CON TACTED..

DEVAN WRIGHT, PART TIME EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING A PIECE OF FREIGHT THAT WAS ON TOP OF THE DRUMS. HE STOPPED THE HI-LO IN FRONT OF THE DRUMS TO ADJUST HIS FORKS. WHEN HE GOT OFF OF THE HI-LO HIS ARM HIT THE GEAR CAUSING THE FORKLIFT TO MOVE FORWARD AND PUNCTURE THE DRUM. SAW DUST WAS PLACED ON THE SPILLED LIQUID AND THE TWO PUNCTURED DRUMS WERE CONTAINED IN SALVAGE DRUMS. THE SAW DUST WAS ALSO CONTAINED IN SALVAGE DRUMS DEVAN  WAS RE EVALUATED AND RETRAINED ON THE HI-LO TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES.

DON WILLIAMS WAS LOADING THIS SHIPMENT OFF THE DOCK ON TO TRL. 313-8929. WHEN BACKING OUT OF THE TRL HE BACKED INTO THIS SHIPMENT CAUSING TO SPILL. DRIVER WAS RETRAINED ON FORK LIFT, AND WILL RECEIVE DISPLINARY ACTION, IN THE FORM OF A LETTER OF INSTRUCTION WHICH WILL BE PLACED IN HIS PERSONAL FILE.
PAIL WAS CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT CAUSING ABOUT 3 OZ TO LEAK.  THE PAIL ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM FOR PROPER HANDLING.

column168: JACKSON, ICTF SECURITY, REPORTED CONTAINER POCU 001279, PLACARDED POISONOUS AND LOCATED DOCKSIDE, WAS LEAKING WITH NO FURTHER INFORMATION AVAILABLE. MIKE JOHNSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MGR JOHNSON REPORTED THE CONTAINER PLACARDED CORROSIVE, UN2030, AND SECONDARY PLACARD POISONOUS, WAS LEAKING FIVE TO SIX DROPS EVERY THREE SECONDS FROM THE BACK OF THE CONTAINER.  THE LEAKED PRODUCT HAD A PH OF 14 AND WAS CONTAINED.  A BAYER CORP SEAL , 183350 WAS ON THE CONTAINER.  DON, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED, AND HE NOTIFIED BILL BURKET, BAYER CORP.  THEY BOTH CONFERRED WITH MR JOHNSON WHO REPORTED TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED FOR A RESPONSE AND THE LOAD WAS SHOWN TO BE FREIGHT OF ALL KINDS.  MR. BURKET REPORTED HE WOULD OBTAIN DETAILED INFORMATION ON THE CONTENTS AND PROVIDE IT TO MR. JOHNSON.  CHEMTREC REPORT NUMBER 04132001070. MGR JOHNSON REPORTED THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED AND THERE WERE NO WATERWAYS EFFECTED.  TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL, UPRR CONTRACTOR, WAS ON SCENE. COUNTY, CITY, STATE, AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. MGR JOHNSON REPORTED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS ONE DRUM PUNCTURED BY A NAIL, RELEASING 30 GALLONS OF MATERIAL.  THE CONTRACTOR ADVISED THAT THE CONTAINER WOULD BE RELEASED AFTER ALL CLEAN UP OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED.

column168: ON 041501 AT APPROXIMATELY 8 A.M. MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER, WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER OBSERVED THE PAINT WAS BLISTERED ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAR FROM THE TOP TO THE BOTTOM.  THERE WERE MULTIPLE STAINS ON THE ASPHALT WHERE THE MATERIAL AND PAINT HAD DRIPPED FROM THE CAR. REEDER HAD THE CAR MOVED TO A SAFE LOCATION AND NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER TO RESPOND.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED WITH A CREW TO WASH THE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED ON A PLASTIC SHEET AND TAKEN FOR DISPOSAL.  THE STAINS ON THE ASPHALT WERE WASHED WITH CHLORINE BLEACH TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED PHENOL. AT APPROXIMATELY 4 P.M. REEDER RECEIVED ANOTHER CALL FROM THE YARD DIRECTOR, TROY SLINKARD.    SLINKARD ADVISED THAT THE AFTERNOON SHIFT PERSONNEL WERE COMPLAINING OF ODORS NEAR THE SPILL AREA.  SLINKARD VISITED THE SITE CONFIRMED THE PRESENCE OF ODORS, THOUGH HE COULD NOT DETERMINE THEIR SOURCE.  SLINKARD REQUESTED THAT THE AREA BE FURTHER CLEANED. REEDER HIRED PAT BAKER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE TO RESPOND TO THE AREA WITH A PRESSURE WASHER TO CLEAN THE WALKWAY ALONG THE TRACK AND THE BALLAST IN THE AREA OF THE SPILL.  BAKER COMPANY USED A SOLUTION OF WATER AND SODA ASH TO RINSE THE BALLAST.  THIS TASK WAS COMPLETED AROUND 8 P.M.

column168: ON 4/18/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 11 A.M. PORT PETROLEUM ENTERED THE LOADING AREA TO OFF LOAD 3000 GALLONS OF MINERAL SPIRITS INTO OUR HOLDING TANK.  ED COX, OUR QUALITY CONTROL TECHNICIAN OBSERVED THE PROPER CONNECTION TO OUR LINE AND ALLOWED THE PROCESS TO CONTINUE.  AFTER EMPTYING ONE COMPARTMENT OF THE TANKER, THOMAS RABBITT, THE DRIVER FOR PORT PETROLEUM DISCONNECTED THE FITTING ON THE COMPARTMENT HE HAD EMPTIED AND CONNECTED THE FITTING AND HOSE TO THE COMPARTMENT CONTAINING THE REMAINDER OF MINERAL SPIRITS.  AFTER ENGAGING THE PUMP MR. RABBITT NOTICED A PROBLEM WITH THE METER ON THE PUMP AND IMMEDIATELY CHECKED THE CONNECTION AND NOTICED THAT THE FITTING HAD RELEASED FROM THE TANKER CAUSING MINERAL SPIRITS TO RELEASE ONTO THE ASPHALT LOADING AREA.  AFTER CLOSING THE VALVE ON THE TANKER TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER RELEASE MR. RABBITT NOTIFIED MR. COX AND HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE PROPER PERSONNEL TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  HERB WARD AND MARLOW JORDAN CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH ABSORBENT BOOMS AND PADS AND PLACED THEM IN A MARKED CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL.  WHILE THE RELEASE WAS BEING CONTAINED, MR. RABBITT NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCHER AT PORT PETROLEUM MR. AL BEHR WHOM IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED CLIFF BERRY, INC. A HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTRACTOR.  A CREW FROM CLIFF BERRY INC. ARRIVED AND COVERED THE AREA WITH PORTLAND CEMENT TO FURTHER ABSORB ANY REMAINING MATERIAL.  AFTER APPLYING THE PORTLAND CEMENT THEY SCRAPED UP THE RESIDUE AND DRUMMED IT OFF FOR DISPOSAL.  AT 1:15PM ON 04/18/01 I NOTIFIED KATHERINE BRAMLADGE WITH THE BROWARD COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION OF THE RELEASE.  AT 1:30 P.M. ON 4/18/01 I NOTIFIED ANGELA MATTHEWS WITH THE STATE OF FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION OF THE RELEASE.  AT 7:20 A.M. ON 4/19/01 I NOTIFIED MR. THURMAN AT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER OF THE RELEASE.  THE REPORT # FROM THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER IS 563357.  THE RELEASE WAS NOT REPORTED IMMEDIATELY TO THE LOCAL AND STATE AGENCIES DUE TO THE FACT THAT I WAS AT A HAZARDOUS WASTE MANAGEMENT WORKSHOP AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT.  I REPORTED LATE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER BECAUSE I DID NOT KNOW WE ARE CONSIDERED A TERMINAL FACILITY.
